<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers 17, Athletics 16  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MARSHALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- The Texas Rangers overcame an eight-run
deficit for the first time in team history, rallying past the
Oakland Athletics 17-16 Friday night on pinch-hitter Mike Lamb's
RBI single in the bottom of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   On a night in which neither team took batting practice because
of morning showers, the A's and Rangers combined for six homers,
six doubles and 37 hits in the majors' highest-scoring game of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which wasted an early 5-0 lead, trailed 15-7 after six
innings and was down 16-10 before tying it with a six-run eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers loaded the bases with one out in the ninth on a
single, walk and an error by pitcher Jeff Tam (0-2). Lamb singled
home Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland (1-1), the only one of 10 pitchers to not allow a
run, worked the ninth for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs tied an AL record when all 18 starters scored,
matching a feat accomplished by the Boston Red Sox and Philadelphia
Athletics on June 29, 1950. The major league record for players
scoring in one game is 22, set by the Philadelphia Phillies and
Chicago Cubs on Aug. 25, 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sheldon drove in four runs for Texas, which had 21 hits.
Ben Grieve drove in four runs for the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, coming off a 14-5 win over Kansas City on Wednesday,
got home runs by Frank Menechino, Ramon Hernandez, Jeremy Giambi,
Adam Piatt and Terrence Long.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez homered for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland trailed 5-0 in the second, tied it in the fifth, and
then fell behind 7-5 in the bottom half. The A's opened a 15-7 lead
with five runs each in the sixth and seventh innings.
</P>
<P>
   With Texas trailing by six in the eighth, Rafael Palmeiro had a
two-run single off Doug Jones, and Luis Alicea and Sheldon each hit
two-run singles off Mike Magnante.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver, staked to a 5-0 lead in the second, left after
five innings ahead 7-5. Reliever Matt Perisho allowed 10 runs, five
hits and four walks in the next two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho walked the bases loaded in the sixth and Grieve hit a
three-run double to the gap in left-center for an 8-7 lead. Giambi,
recalled from Triple-A Sacramento before the game, followed with a
two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Piatt had a two-run homer and Miguel Tejada added a two-run
double in a five-run seventh that made it 15-7. Three runs were
unearned after left fielder Chad Curtis dropped Olmedo Saenz's fly
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Texas took a 5-0 lead in the second off Mark Mulder. Sheldon,
filling in for an injured David Segui, had a two-run single and
Curtis had a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland closed in a three-run fourth that included Menechino's
homer, and Hernandez tied it at 5 with a two-run homer in the
fifth. Palmeiro and Ruben Mateo hit RBI singles in the bottom half.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez had his fifth consecutive multihit game, finishing
going 3-for-5 with a solo homer in the seventh.
Notes: Segui was scratched from the lineup with a strained right
hip flexor sustained Thursday night against Tampa Bay. ... The
Athletics are 10-4 on the road, 5-10 at home. ... The game included
two pickoffs at first base in which the runner took off early.
Piatt got caught in the second inning and Texas' Tom Evans was
erased in the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0033 </TRAILER>
