<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York has a new budget, 35 days late  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Being late 35 days sounds like a lot, but by
New York's standards of overdue state budget adoptions, this year's
tardiness was not so bad.
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly and Senate adopted a $77.5 billion budget on
Friday for the 2000-01 fiscal year which began on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 16th straight year the budget wasn't in place on
time. But except for 1998, when the budget was adopted on April 14,
this year's budget is the earliest since 1993. Included in those
years of budget-adoption futility were numbing impasses in 1999 and
1997 which stretched to Aug. 4 each year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did a budget that I believe is one of the best budgets that
we've enacted on behalf of the people of this state certainly since
I've been leader and maybe since I've been in the Senate,'' said
state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a 24-year Senate
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The new budget contains a series of firsts: the highest-ever
increase in state aid for public schools of $1.2 billion; a
first-in-the nation deduction from state income taxes for college
costs; the largest-ever proposed state bond act, $3.8 billion to
aid transportation, to be placed before voters in November; the
first concerted effort to rein in state borrowing practices; and
expansions of benefits to highest-ever levels of the EPIC
prescription drug program for the elderly and the Tuition
Assistance Program for college students.
</P>
<P>
   The new budget increases spending in the state's general fund --
comprised of funds the state raises itself through taxes and fees --
by just under 5 percent and overall by just under 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a Democrat who may run for
governor in 2002, said increasing spending above the rate of
inflation at the same time the state was approving another $3
billion in non-voter-approved ''backdoor'' debt showed how out of
touch state leaders are.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes it seems as if New York is in its own little
Twilight Zone,'' McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall also deride the debt reform initiatives as riddled with
loopholes and meaningless provisions -- and immediately drew an
attack from Michael McKeon, spokesman for Gov. George Pataki, who
accused McCall of calling publicly for debt reform but doing
nothing practical to see that it was instituted.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki defended the ''fiscally responsible'' budget. It makes
''prudent'' contributions into rainy day funds so that if the
economy goes sour or some other fiscal disaster besets New York,
the state can weather the storm, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   There was little debate over any of the budget bills since most
of the high points of the spending plan had been known for weeks.
The state Assembly took just over five hours to pass the 13-bill
budget package late Thursday and early Friday, with much of the
time taken up by closed-door conferences or members waiting for
bills to be brought before them for votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate worked a few hours Thursday night and returned into
session Friday morning, where it took just 40 minutes to approve
the final seven budget bills.
</P>
<P>
   While vetoes by Pataki are possible, the governor was involved
in negotiating all significant aspects of the budget and is not
known to have any major objections.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is my understanding that he will not do any wholesale
vetoes,'' Sheldon Silver, the Democratic speaker in the Assembly,
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno estimated that about 98 percent of the budget consisted of
bills the governor sent back to the Legislature in recent days,
indicating his acceptance of the provisions. The rest originated in
the Legislature. Bruno called the budget ''fairly veto-proof.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Bruno and Silver devised a budget without Pataki's
input and the governor vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars worth
of legislative spending initiatives. Silver vowed to get Pataki
involved in the legislative negotiating process to avoid a repeat
of that veto-happy budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-06-00 0041 </TRAILER>
