<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki: I am backing cost-of-living pension increases  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki says he favors pensioners
of state and local governments getting annual pension increases to
keep up with the cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki announced Friday he has reviewed the report of a task
force he created in June 1999 to study the cost-of-living issue and
agrees with its recommendation to institute automatic and permanent
COLAs.
</P>
<P>
   ''With our healthy economy and the strong performance of the
pension systems, the timing is right to address the COLA situation
and I look forward to working with the Legislature on this,''
Pataki said in a statement released by this office.
</P>
<P>
   Public employee unions and groups of retirees have lobbied hard
in recent years for cost-of-living increases, noting that their
pension fund has never been worth more. The state's Common
Retirement Fund has increased from $63.4 billion in 1995 to about
$120 billion today.
</P>
<P>
   The fund covers about 600,000 current public employees and
290,000 retirees.
</P>
<P>
   To this time, Pataki has been sympathetic to the pensioners'
arguments, but said he wanted to see what his task force
recommended before taking a position.
</P>
<P>
   Pensioners did get pension ''supplementation'' in 1995 and 1998
-- one-time benefit increases -- but they have been pushing for
benefits to go up annually based on some gauge of rising living
expenses such as the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   A pro-COLA rally by current and retired public employees is
scheduled for Tuesday in Albany. Organizers said they expected as
many as 10,000 people at the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is truly wonderful news,'' said Denyce Duncan Lacy,
spokeswoman for the Public Employees Federation union. ''Those are
things that PEF has been saying ought to happen for years. It
sounds like the governor is agreeing with us. It is long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller H. Carl McCall, the sole trustee of the state
and local retiree pension fund, said the pension task force's
recommendations echo many of the proposals he has made for
increasing benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''My guiding principles have been that any COLA should be
permanent, automatic, reliable and affordable, and I am heartened
that these ideas were adopted by the task force,'' McCall said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those on the pension task force were Adam Barsky, director
of the New York City Mayor's Office of Management and Budget;
former state Budget Director Patrick Bulgaro; Danny Donohue,
president of the Civil Service Employees Association; Denis Hughes,
president of the state AFL-CIO; and Cynthia Wilson, president of
the Retired Public Employees Association.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was chaired by Linda Angello, director of Pataki's
Office of Employee Relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
