<HEADLINE> No prescription needed for hypodermic needles  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJudge agrees anthrax vaccine unsafe; halts court martial
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG (AP) -- The Armed Forces have been dragged into the 21st
century, suggests a retired air force sergeant whose refusal to
take an anthrax vaccine was validated Friday by Canada's chief
military judge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can defend our Canadian rights, but we should be able to
partake in them also,'' Mike Kipling said moments after he and his
supporters jubilantly cheered the decision of Col. Guy Brais to end
Kipling's court martial before it even started.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great for Mike Kipling and it signals a new era in human
rights for enlisted men and women,'' said Jay Prober, the civilian
lawyer Kipling decided to hire instead of accepting free military
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Brais agreed with the defense that the vaccine Kipling was asked
to take in 1998 in Kuwait during the second Gulf War could have
been unsafe, based on evidence presented in court, and therefore
his common law and Charter rights were jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   Retired colonel Michel Drapeau, a frequent critic of Canada's
military who writes for Esprit de Corps magazine, hailed Kipling as
an honorable soldier who did the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Drapeau pointed out that Kipling resigned in an attempt to end
the matter and avoid court martial for disobeying an order, but the
military decided to pursue him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Army spokesman Capt. Brian Martin said from Ottawa that no
policy changes will take effect until the military has time to
examine the decision.
------
Chretien calls U.N. designation of Clayoquot Sound ''Canadian
success story''
</P>
<P>
   TOFINO, British Columbia (AP) -- Clayoquot Sound, the site of one
of the largest demonstrations of civil disobedience in Canadian
history, is a ''great Canadian success story,'' Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien was at Pacific Rim National Park as the sound was
declared a United Nations biosphere reserve, a place for
sustainable economic development, research, education and training.
</P>
<P>
   Logging in Clayoquot Sound on the west coast of Vancouver Island
had been vigorously opposed by environmental groups in the 1980s
and early 1990s. The dispute culminated in a massive protest in
1993, the so-called War in the Woods.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 protesters were arrested along logging roads.
</P>
<P>
   Canada was given an international black eye as the issue was
taken up by celebrities such as Australian rock band Midnight Oil
and Robert Kennedy Jr., an environmental lawyer and the son of
slain U.S. senator Robert Kennedy. Both appeared at the site during
the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Clearcut logging ended in the sound after the protests.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. designation was treated as a victory Friday by
environmentalists who attended the ceremonies.
--------
Love Bug brings calls for national cyber police agency
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A seemingly continuous stream of global computer
viruses like this week's so-called love bug is triggering calls for
a national cyber-police squad to jump on Internet attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Gaylen Duncan, president of the Information Technology
Association of Canada, said a Canada-wide police force is needed to
track down and prosecute computer hackers and virus creators.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's doable,'' Duncan said Friday from Toronto. ''But it takes
a hit squad that moves at the speed of light.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a six-month investigation, this is not a two-year
prosecution. This kind of stuff has to move within the week,'' said
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan said the pressure is on the international business
community to demand governments around the world create a global
treaty to help prosecute offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Teeple, in charge of the RCMP's technical security branch,
said a new Canadian information protection center is likely to be
established. This will follow September's tabling of a federal task
force report on the protection of critical infrastructure.
------
Endangered list continues to grow with no end in sight, experts
say
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Scientists have added 14 Canadian species,
including the southern-mountain tailed frog of British Columbia, to
a list of animals and plants endangered or at risk.
</P>
<P>
   And biologists warned Friday that there's no end in sight to
additions to the endangered-species list because of pollution and
development.
</P>
<P>
   ''This list will grow and it will continue to grow,'' David
Green, chairman of an independent committee on the status on
endangered wildlife, said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be more species that become in peril.''
</P>
<P>
   A panel in Ottawa assessed 140 species this week, including
mammals, plants, amphibians, reptiles, fish, butterflies and
mollusks. The majority remained in the same-risk category they were
in last year.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists and wildlife experts have drafted an annual report on
at-risk animals and plants since 1978.
