<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani and Clinton court Liberal Party  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton is courting the
leadership of New York's Liberal Party even though one of Senate
rival Rudolph Giuliani's top political advisers is the party's
boss.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and the New York City mayor were to make separate
appearances this morning before the party's policy committee in New
York City. An endorsement decision from the party's full state
committee could come in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Kim Serafin noted Friday that no
Democrat has been elected governor or senator in New York without
Liberal Party backing since the party's founding in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Clinton's advisers have said they hold out little
hope they can win the Liberal Party nod given that party boss
Raymond Harding is a Giuliani confidant. They have also been trying
to put the best face on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't need all these third-party lines,'' a defiant state
Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope said Tuesday on MSNBC's
''Hardball'' program.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview with The Associated Press, Hope said
that while chances of a Clinton endorsement by the Liberal Party
were 'remote ... we assume that none of these institutions are
monolithic and you never know what's around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Liberal Party members said Friday that the Giuliani
forces shouldn't count on walking off with the party's endorsement
and that it may go to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely going to be a dogfight, but I'm really very
confident -- very, very confident,'' said Clinton supporter Joe
Laux, a Liberal Party vice chairman and a member of its policy
committee that was to interview the candidates today.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the intrigue is the expectation that the Liberal Party
will have Vice President Al Gore at the top of its ticket. But that
can only be accomplished with Gore's agreement. The vice
president's New York staff and Clinton's are extremely close.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the issue of whether Giuliani will even stay in
the race. He announced April 27 that he was suffering from prostate
cancer. The mayor said he would decide whether to stay in the race
after discussing treatment options with his doctors. Aides to the
mayor say a decision could come by the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Third party endorsements can be critical in New York in close
races. Polls show the Senate race to be just that with Clinton and
Giuliani in it.
</P>
<P>
   New York, unlike other states, allows major party candidates to
count votes they receive on third-party ballot lines. In fact,
Republican George Pataki beat incumbent Democrat Mario Cuomo in the
1994 governor's race on the strength of the vote from the
Conservative Party line.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the leader of the Conservative Party, Michael Long,
is balking at endorsing Republican Giuliani because of his ties to
the Liberal Party and his support for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both Clinton and Giuliani appeared at a forum in
Buffalo for Senate candidates April 29 staged by the New York wing
of the national Reform Party. At that event, however, Clinton told
Independence Party leaders that she would not accept their
endorsement if they nominated Pat Buchanan as their presidential
candidate. Giuliani said later that he would probably not run on
the line either if Buchanan were at the top of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Giuliani camp launched a new television
advertisement. Aides said the 30-second spot would air statewide
for about two weeks at a cost that could top $1 million. The mayor
has had campaign ads running off and on for months.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's campaign launched its first statewide TV ad on
Wednesday, also for a two-week run. It is expected to cost about
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the new TV ads attacks the opposing candidate,
although Giuliani's has thinly veiled barbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be a senator because I was born in this state,'' he
says in it.
</P>
<P>
   Until January, Clinton had never lived in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Later today, President and Mrs. Clinton were to attend a wedding
in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the first couple will be the stars at a
$250-a-person, fund-raising event in Little Rock to benefit her
campaign. About 300 people are expected to attend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-06-00 0044 </TRAILER>
