<HEADLINE> Clinton, Senate Democrats Meet  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGTON, Pa. (AP) -- President Clinton met with Senate
Democrats at a plush resort in the mountains of western
Pennsylvania, spending about two hours talking about pending
legislation, this year's presidential race and the party's future
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The event was closed to the press, but White House deputy press
secretary Jim Kennedy said about 20 senators attended the two-day
annual issues retreat, which ends today at the 2,600-acre complex
with tennis courts, two golf courses and European-style inn.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president spoke for a little while, talking about his
education tour this week and then he took questions and they
engaged in a discussion of a variety of domestic and international
issues -- everything from Russia to racial relations,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Senate Democratic Leader Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., called
it a strategy session to discuss such issues as health care, gun
control, raising the minimum wage and juvenile justice. Panel
discussion topics included technology in the 21st century, privacy
issues and arms control.
</P>
<P>
   ''They talked a little bit about politics, as you might
imagine,'' Kennedy said. ''They talked about the fact that he had
been here (at retreats) all eight years.'' And, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., joked that he hoped the president would return
next year as a ''Senate spouse'' -- a reference to first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton's bid for the Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans hold similar sessions, Republican National
Committee spokesman Chris Paulitz characterized the retreat as no
more than a huddle to coach Vice President Al Gore on an ''attack
strategy'' against his expected GOP presidential opponent, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left before Gore arrived to address the senators at
dinner Friday night. The president traveled to Lancaster, Va., to
attend the wake for the son of a White House employee who works in
the first family's residence.
</P>
</TEXT>
