<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Ireland Plan Faces Hurdles  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A surprise Anglo-Irish plan for
resurrecting Northern Ireland's Catholic-Protestant administration
has raised hopes at a critical hour in peacemaking, but faces
fundamental hurdles in the days and weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 hours of talks with local parties, the British and
Irish prime ministers Tony Blair and Bertie Ahern announced late
Friday that they wanted to transfer power back to local hands on
May 22 -- two years to the day after all of Ireland strongly backed
the landmark Good Friday peace accord. They challenged politicians
within the suspended four-party coalition to shift their fixed
positions and make lasting compromise possible.
</P>
<P>
   But the province's major British Protestant party, the Ulster
Unionists, emphasized that any emerging deal would hinge on whether
the Irish Republican Army agreed to disarm, otherwise they wouldn't
resume sharing power alongside the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party.
</P>
<P>
   That unresolved argument forced Britain to suspend the
coalition's powers in February after just 11 weeks in office. The
IRA, in response, broke off all contact with the province's
independent disarmament commission.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their new formula, Ahern and Blair said one of the
Good Friday accord's goals -- to achieve the total disarmament of
the IRA and outlawed pro-British groups by May 22 -- should be
extended to June 2001. They suggested that verbal commitments from
the armed groups to disarm would be a sufficient starting point.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governments believe that the paramilitary organizations
must now, for their part, urgently state that they will put their
arms completely and verifiably beyond use,'' the prime ministers
said in their joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd be very disappointed if the response from the
paramilitaries was not extremely positive,'' Ahern added.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the two governments said they expected the IRA to
issue a new policy statement this weekend confirming the outlawed
group's intention to resume talks with the disarmament commission.
</P>
<P>
   And in hopes of encouraging newfound IRA flexibility on the
issue, Blair suggested that Britain would pursue a policy of troop
withdrawals and army installation closures if the IRA began
scrapping its hidden weapons stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams lauded the prime ministers'
unexpected initiative as ''a very decisive moment'' in efforts to
promote accommodation between the province's long-competing British
Protestant and Irish Catholic blocs.
</P>
<P>
   But Adams, a reputed former IRA commander, declined to comment
on what the group might do and asserted Sinn Fein's right to hold
two posts within the suspended 12-member Cabinet even if the IRA
didn't promise to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Just as importantly, it remained unclear whether Ulster Unionist
leader David Trimble would be able to rally his already bitterly
divided party behind an initiative that would postpone the deadline
for IRA disarmament once again.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, weakened by an unexpectedly strong leadership challenge
last month, also is vulnerable to criticism from his hard-line
rivals for Protestant votes, the Democratic Unionists. That party
holds two posts within the suspended Cabinet -- even though it
opposes sharing power with Sinn Fein under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these obstacles, President Clinton appealed to both
sides to achieve both power-sharing and disarmament as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''I urge the parties and paramilitary organizations to seize
this opportunity to realize these goals in order to restore lasting
peace to the people of Northern Ireland,'' Clinton said in
Lancaster, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0124 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vieques Protesters Vow To Return  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Abraham ''Yungo'' Velez tried -- and
failed -- to run the blockade around the U.S. Navy's Vieques bombing
range with his 27-foot fishing boat.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I'll try again,'' he said cheerfully after relating his
escapade Friday to chuckling fishermen at El Yate Bar. ''They can't
stay out there forever.''
</P>
<P>
   On Vieques, people faced the prospect of renewed Navy
bombardment with determination and pride at having won a promise
from the world's only superpower that, if they choose, the Navy
will be gone in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Many insisted that the federal raid Thursday that dislodged 216
protesters from the Atlantic fleet training ground they had
occupied for a year was a temporary setback.
</P>
<P>
   To prove it, demonstrators were hard at work again -- setting up
a new camp next to the training ground, planning meetings and
Masses and vowing to return to the range to halt more exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters occupied the Navy's 60-year-old range in April 1999
after a civilian guard was killed in an accidental bombing. They
stood in the way of a Jan. 31 accord between President Clinton and
Gov. Pedro Rossello allowing the Navy to resume limited training
with inert bombs until 2003, with a Vieques referendum to decide
whether the Navy can stay longer and use live ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy argues that Vieques is vital to national security
because it is the only place that air, land and sea forces can
train simultaneously with live munitions before deploying abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The raid touched off protests outside a federal courthouse in
historic Old San Juan on Friday and forced police to beef up
security at U.S. Army and Navy bases, federal offices and post
offices on the main island of Puerto Rico. National Guard troops
protected water and electricity plants.
</P>
<P>
   Several militants smashed the window of a car carrying former
Gov. Luis A. Ferre as he arrived at the courthouse for a dedication
ceremony. Ferre was not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Protests by students -- and in some cases their professors -- shut
down classes at colleges in the cities of Ponce and Bayamon and
disrupted many classes at the University of Puerto Rico's main
campus in San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   In Vieques, protesters pitched a blue tarpaulin and began
hanging up new anti-Navy placards near a police roadblock half a
mile from where U.S. soldiers were dismantling their old camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they think they've stopped us, they're wrong,'' said Norma
Torres, a 53-year-old high school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the detained protesters were back in Vieques within
hours of the raid, whisked home from Roosevelt Roads Naval Station
by a flotilla of fishing boats flying the Puerto Rican flag.
Hundreds of people on shore cheered wildly as the incoming boats
launched red flares into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters said they would redouble their political efforts to
expel the Navy, using the attention the arrests garnered -- as well
as demonstrations in the United States -- to help influence U.S.
lawmakers and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   They questioned how long the Navy could keep its training ground
sealed, even with Marine patrols, helicopter overflights and Coast
Guard ships enforcing a three-mile-wide security zone around the
range.
</P>
<P>
   The training ground's 20 miles of coastline are pocked with
small, sheltered coves. Protesters have repeatedly cut through the
five-mile chain-link fence on its western boundary, sometimes using
horses to travel through brush that is impassable for military
Humvees.
</P>
<P>
   Activist Carlos Zenon claimed Friday that seven people,
including two of his sons, were hiding in the range. The Navy said
it knew of no holdouts and was planning to rapidly resume training.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mapepe is hidden, protected in the hills!'' protesters at the
roadside camp chanted, referring to an alleged ''secret'' camp in
the range.
</P>
<P>
   Even non-protesters said they doubted the battle had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the Navy will go back and reclaim its land and the
protesters will head back as well,'' said Federico Campos, a doctor
in the town of Isabel Segunda. ''It's going to start all over
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Athlete Hangs Himself  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WELLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Five Columbine High basketball players
gathered on a home patio court to shoot hoops as they struggled to
grasp why their close friend and teammate committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Greg Barnes, 17, who lost one of his best friends and saw
a teacher die in last year's Columbine bloodbath, hanged himself
Thursday while classmates went to school, said neighbor Leonard
Purer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not know if Columbine caused this, but I do know he was
upset by it. All the students were upset by it,'' said Purer, who
has known the family for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   A CD, set to replay continuously, blasted a song by the group
Blink 182 with the lyrics, ''You'll be sorry when I'm gone,'' and
''I never thought I'd die alone,'' said teammate David Mitchell, an
exchange student from Melbourne, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talked to him the night before, and it didn't seem like
anything was wrong,'' he said Friday as he took a break from the
game on teammate Brian Deidel's court. ''We talked about the usual
stuff, girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Deidel, also a childhood friend of Barnes, said, ''I just didn't
believe it. It was horrible. It made me mad. Mad at Greg.''
</P>
<P>
   Grief counselors cautioned against automatically linking Barnes'
death to the Columbine shootings, noting teen-agers cope with a
great deal of pressure. Suicide is the third-leading cause of death
for people ages 15 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' death came just two weeks after the anniversary of the
massacre. It was the second suicide among friends or relatives of
the victims since October, and the latest in a series of tragedies
that have sent the Columbine community reeling.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators would not say whether Barnes left a note and gave
no additional details. Six counselors came to Columbine Friday, and
substitute teachers were on call to fill in for staff members who
wanted to stay home, said Jefferson County School District
spokesman Rick Kaufman. Many students skipped school.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a somber mood at Columbine High School,'' said Kaufman,
who declined to give details about the death.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's office and the Jefferson County coroner also
declined to provide details. ''Some things should remain
confidential to the family,'' Coroner Nancy Bodelson said.
</P>
<P>
   On April 20, 1999, two teen-age gunmen killed 12 Columbine
classmates and a teacher and wounded 23 people before committing
suicide in the worst school shooting rampage in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was in a science room when the gunmen opened fire. He
told Sports Illustrated he saw teacher Dave Sanders ''take two
shots, right in front of me'' as he watched the rampage through a
window in the door. Barnes was also a good friend of victim Matt
Kechter.
</P>
<P>
   ''Matt always waited by the mailbox for his little brother to
come home from school,'' Barnes told The Associated Press after the
shooting. ''He was the most innocent person I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the massacre, most in the Columbine community have lived
with grief as a constant companion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not know if Columbine caused this, but I do know he was
upset by it. All the students were upset by it,'' Purer said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of Anne Marie Hochhalter, a student paralyzed in the
shooting, walked into a pawnshop in October, asked to see a gun,
loaded it and shot herself to death. On Valentine's Day, two
Columbine sweethearts were shot to death in a sandwich shop.
</P>
<P>
   At a bagel shop near the school Friday, C.J. Reeh, 72, and his
wife, Irene, stared in disbelief at newspaper accounts of Barnes'
death.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what to think. We thought it would be the last
when the mother shot herself. We don't know what's going to be
next,'' said C.J. Reeh.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 Barnes, who averaged 26.2 points a game in the
season that ended in March, had drawn interest from several
universities, including Harvard, Yale and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 31 points in Columbine's loss during the state
quarterfinal playoff game in March. The Denver Post and the Denver
Rocky Mountain News named him to their all-state teams, and Barnes
would have been the top player in the state next year, according to
two coaches whose teams played Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never thought Greg was the kind of person who would do
something like this. He had everything going for him,'' said Jason
Brehm, 17, a junior who shared a history class with Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wasn't the real typical jock who would throw the little guy
around. He didn't try to be the best at everything, except
basketball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
