<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Day one of services marking cardinal's death  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- During his 16 years in New York, Cardinal John
O'Connor was on the altar at St. Patrick's Cathedral for an
assortment of funerals and memorial services: for city heroes, for
New York Yankee great Joe DiMaggio, for the victims of TWA Flight
800 and Swissair Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   Now his chair sits empty, and it is O'Connor's time to be
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 mourners silently walked past his casket Friday
at the start of a four-day farewell to the cardinal, who died
Wednesday night at the age of 80. His body was returned Friday
afternoon to his beloved cathedral, arriving with a full police
escort.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was without a doubt the quintessential homebody,'' said
Bishop Patrick Sheridan, vicar general of St. Patrick's, during a
special rite observing O'Connor's final homecoming. ''His work is
done, and now he's home.''
</P>
<P>
   The remains of O'Connor, who conducted countless memorials for
New York heroes both famed and obscure in the grand cathedral, were
brought up the church steps by eight pallbearers on a warm spring
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Organ music swelled and the church bells rang as the casket was
carried inside. The congregation sang a hymn, ''Now From the
Heavens Descending,'' as the pallbearers -- joined by a phalanx of
priests, nuns and altar servers -- slowly marched through the
church.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-minute service marked O'Connor's return to the Manhattan
church where he presided for 16 years after swapping Scranton, Pa.,
for a position as the nation's highest-profile Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ''He held fast to the traditions handed to him,'' said a teary
Ralph Giordano, 23, who stood on the sidewalk opposite St.
Patrick's. ''I trusted him for that reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's dark wood coffin was carried through the ornate
brass doors of the Fifth Avenue church, then brought up the aisle
and placed at the front of the main altar.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is home now, in his beloved cathedral, the object of our
esteem,'' Sheridan said. ''May God grant him eternal rest.''
</P>
<P>
   A steady flow of mourners -- estimated at about 10,000 -- was soon
marching past the open casket to bid a final goodbye to the late
spiritual leader of the archdiocese's 2.4 million faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt inspired and touched,'' said Frank Zizzo of Levittown,
N.Y., whose wife Josephine visited the casket with him. ''He looked
incredibly at peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's body was brought down Fifth Avenue from an Upper
East Side funeral home with an escort of police motorcycles. To the
left of the cathedral doors, the Sisters of Life -- an order of nuns
founded in 1991 by the cardinal -- stood awaiting his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the service, the lid of the coffin was removed to
show the cardinal lying peacefully inside its red velvet. His hands
-- holding a white rosary -- were folded across his white vestments.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's body will lie in the cathedral all day Saturday
and Sunday. The funeral Mass was scheduled for Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, a special Mass was celebrated by the cardinal's
former secretary, Bishop James McCarthy of the St. Elizabeth Ann
Seton parish in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some have asked what will be his legacy,'' McCarthy said.
''May I suggest one: he saved lives -- the lives of the unborn, the
lives of the poor, the lives of those in war-torn nations.''
</P>
<P>
   By the start of the earlier service, the church was nearly full
and more than 1,000 people stood opposite the church. Police
barricades were erected on the cathedral's north and south sides to
handle the expected lines of mourners.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-deep crowds on the sidewalk included a fair amount of
tourists and passers-by along with the mourners. ''Who is coming
out of the church?'' asked Eszter Stampel, 21, a Hungarian student.
''Who is going in?''
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the usual two sign-in books at the front of the
church, an additional 10 were placed for guests to write their
names. The front of the church was festooned with black and purple
bunting.
</P>
<P>
   Following the four-day farewell, O'Connor's body will remain at
St. Patrick's. The cardinal will be interred in the crypt beneath
the cathedral's altar, where all the previous archbishops of New
York are buried.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Toussaint, a former slave who could become the church's
first black American saint, is also interred there. O'Connor
supported efforts to win his sainthood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-06-00 0134 </TRAILER>
