<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Testimony on Tripp Limited  </HEADLINE>
By GREG TOPPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLICOTT CITY, Md. (AP) -- Maryland prosecutors must consider
whether to proceed with their wiretapping case against Linda Tripp
now that a judge has suppressed virtually all of Monica Lewinsky's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The former White House intern is the star witness in the
criminal case -- and the voice on the other end of Tripp's secretly
recorded conversations about Lewinsky's affair with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp was indicted last July for secretly making a Dec. 22,
1997, tape of Lewinsky and disclosing its contents for editors of
Newsweek magazine in January 1998. Maryland law prohibits
intercepting telephone conversations without both parties' consent.
Prosecutors say Tripp's secret recordings of her talks with
Lewinsky constitute interception.
</P>
<P>
   Howard County Circuit Judge Diane Leasure on Friday ruled that
Lewinsky can testify that she never gave Tripp permission to tape
record their conversations in late 1997. But Lewinsky won't be
allowed to tell a jury that she and Tripp had the December
conversation Tripp is accused of illegally taping.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking back through the evidence to make sure that,
given what she's suppressed, we still have enough to go forward,''
said assistant prosecutor Thomas McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp attorney Joseph Murtha said he was encouraged by the
ruling. ''We will not walk away from this day discouraged in any
sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Tripp repeated her assertion that the
state's case is politically motivated
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the court's ruling today, any action by the prosecution
short of dismissal rises to the level of malicious prosecution,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp received federal immunity for her cooperation with
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. State Prosecutor Stephen
Montanarelli was free to bring state charges against her, but could
not use any evidence Tripp gave Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Leasure ruled that Lewinsky's testimony that she independently
remembered the date of the December conversation was not credible,
and that her recollection was tainted by reading Starr's report to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no question that Ms. Lewinsky, perhaps more so than
any other ... state witnesses, had substantial exposure to Ms.
Tripp's immunized testimony and information that came from Ms.
Tripp as a result of her cooperation'' with Starr's prosecutors,
the judge wrote. ''The defense argues that Ms. Lewinsky is 'bathed
in impermissible taint.' The court agrees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tripp-Lewinsky tapes triggered Starr's investigation of
President Clinton, which led to impeachment proceedings last year.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys argued the judge should dismiss the case
because it was tainted by evidence from the Starr investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Leasure refused to throw out the case, however, because
prosecutors did not let the grand jury hear testimony protected by
Tripp's immunity deal.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Tripp could face 10 years in prison and a $20,000
fine. She is the only major figure in the Clinton sex scandal to
face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Court system: http://www.courts.state.md.us/howard/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Tripp Legal Defense Fund site: http://www.lindatripp.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0135 </TRAILER>
