<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberal Party Sought in N.Y. Race  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton is courting the
leadership of New York's Liberal Party even though one of Rudolph
Giuliani's top political advisers is the party's boss.
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. Senate candidates were to make separate appearances
today before the party's policy committee in New York City. An
endorsement decision from the party's full state committee could
come in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Kim Serafin said Friday that no
Democrat has been elected governor or senator in New York without
Liberal Party backing since the party's founding in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Clinton's advisers have said they hold out little
hope they can win the Liberal Party nod given that party boss
Raymond Harding is a Giuliani confidant. They have also been trying
to put the best face on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope said chances of a
Clinton endorsement by the Liberal Party were remote, but ''we
assume that none of these institutions are monolithic and you never
know what's around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Liberal Party members said Friday that the Giuliani
forces shouldn't count on walking off with the party's endorsement
and that it may go to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely going to be a dogfight, but I'm really very
confident -- very, very confident,'' said Clinton supporter Joe
Laux, a Liberal Party vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the issue of whether Giuliani will even stay in
the race. The Republican announced April 27 that he was suffering
from prostate cancer. Aides to the mayor say a decision about
staying in the campaign could come by the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Third party endorsements can be critical in New York in close
races, and polls show the Senate race to be just that.
</P>
<P>
   New York, unlike other states, allows major party candidates to
count votes they receive on third-party ballot lines. In fact,
Republican George Pataki beat incumbent Democrat Mario Cuomo in the
1994 governor's race on the strength of the vote from the
Conservative Party line.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Giuliani camp launched a new television
advertisement. Aides said the 30-second spot would air statewide
for about two weeks at a cost that could top $1 million. The mayor
has had campaign ads running off and on for months.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's campaign launched its first statewide TV ad on
Wednesday, also for a two-week run. It is expected to cost about
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the new TV ads attacks the opposing candidate,
although Giuliani's has thinly veiled barbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be a senator because I was born in this state,'' he
says in it. Until January, Clinton had never lived in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0139 </TRAILER>
