<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 300 Held Hostage in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations was appealing for
international help in shoring up its beleaguered peacekeeping
mission in Sierra Leone, where an estimated 300 U.N. troops were
held captive and at least four were dead after clashes with rebels.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said officials were trying to rally
regional support to press rebel leader Fodoy Sankoh to release the
hostages. Malian and Nigerian delegations have visited Sankoh in
the capital of Freetown. Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, who has
long had ties to Sankoh, also promised to talk to the rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
   Annan also was trying to mobilize support for reinforcements.
The United States, Britain and France have been approached but have
not offered ground troops. Britain has agreed to provide a
technical support team to help with logistics. Washington was
studying a request for air transport.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations evacuated at least 90 non-essential, non-U.N.
international aid workers and family Friday. But there has been no
serious public discussion yet whether the United Nations would
evacuate any of its 8,700-strong peacekeeping force or its civilian
staff in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, U.N. officials appear resigned to the fact that the
clashes and hostage-taking this week by the Revolutionary United
Front has jeopardized the ''basic premise'' of peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this case, one of the major parties has backed out of the
agreement and has gone and attacked that very peace force. The very
basis of this mission is now in question,'' U.N. spokesman Lt. Col.
Jaswinder Sandhu said Friday in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Four Kenyan U.N. peacekeepers are believed to have been killed
in the clashes and 12 have been injured, Eckhard said. Six rebels
were killed, RUF spokesman Eldred Collins said in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first detained were six U.N. civilians -- a four-man
helicopter crew and two passengers -- who were released Friday from
Kailahun in the east. Liberian President Charles Taylor, a longtime
ally of Sankoh, interceded with Sankoh to call for their release.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 300 U.N. peacekeepers and observers remained
hostage, including a 208-man Zambian contingent seized as it moved
into the central town of Makeni to reinforce U.N. troops who came
under fire earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   The RUF denied it held any hostages and suggested instead that
the troops may have gotten ''lost in the bush'' during fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard said Friday that helicopter surveillance showed rebels
manning some of the 13 armored personnel carriers -- emblazoned with
the U.N. logo on the side -- that were taken from the Zambians.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. mission for Sierra Leone was dispatched in December to
oversee the peace agreement that ended a brutal eight-year civil
war that left the country in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   A power-sharing agreement was reached last July between the
government and the RUF, but this week's fighting has threatened
that. The RUF claims the clashes began because peacekeepers were
forcibly disarming RUF fighters -- a charge U.N. officials deny.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard stressed that U.N. troops had a mandate to use deadly
force to protect themselves and civilians in imminent danger -- but
that any decision on that would be made by the force commander.
</P>
<P>
   ''The emphasis is not to go to war with the RUF,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
