<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson Made Sure Lakers Would Win  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Score this one for the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson made all the right moves during the fifth and
deciding game as the Los Angeles Lakers rolled past the Sacramento
Kings 113-86 Friday night and into the second round of the NBA
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But it was what he did in the two days beforehand that was
probably even more important.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who coached the Chicago Bulls to six NBA championships
in the 1990s, was calm, cool and even a little chippy.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fret over a dicey situation, he embraced it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told them, 'If you can't survive in this kind of adversity
at this point in the playoffs, then we're not going to hang
together as a group. Why even go on?' '' Jackson said a day before
the Lakers avoided one of the biggest upsets in NBA playoff
history.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, who had 14 points, five rebounds and six assists,
said the Lakers ''weren't too much worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Their coach wouldn't allow that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, we were ready, very focused, came out with a lot of
firepower, very aggressive,'' Rice said. ''We wanted to let them
know we meant business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said veterans A.C. Green and Robert Horry, the power
forwards, had to shoot the ball more than they had in two losses in
Sacramento that tied the best-of-five series 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   And so they did.
</P>
<P>
   While Shaquille O'Neal was making his first five shots en route
to a 32-point, 18-rebound performance, Green took four shots in the
first quarter, making one. Horry fired away upon entering the game,
and made his first three shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''You saw A.C. hesitate a couple times before he shot, wide-open
shots,'' Jackson said in his meeting with reporters 90 minutes
before the opening tipoff. ''He should shoot those shots, he's a
veteran. That's what I'm talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher watched from the bench as the Kings led all the way
in winning a 101-88 decision in Game 4. In this game, he was called
upon late in the first quarter, and made four outside jump shots in
as many attempts to help the Lakers take a 59-44 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was no contest after that.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher admitted he was hurt about not playing in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everybody on the team wants to help the team,'' he
said. ''It was tough for me to deal with, I hadn't dealt with that
it 3{ years. It was tough, but you always have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fish is a soldier, he steps up when the coach calls on him,''
said Kobe Bryant, who had 17 points and six assists. ''Tonight, he
was more than ready. Fish's defense ignites his offense. He came
out and got his hands on the ball a couple times, made some big
shots, kept them from sagging in on Shaq. He really stepped up, he
answered the call.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry was 3-of-4 in the opening 24 minutes, giving the Lakers 14
big points from a group of reserves that contributed little in the
two games at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   At one point before the game, Jackson suddenly flashed a big
grin and said, ''This is a game, is that right?''
</P>
<P>
   And he also said, ''I was concerned with a long layoff without a
game and here we are, playing Friday. I think it's better to do it
this way, sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The point? It's better to do whatever it is you're doing. Always
put a positive spin on whatever happens. And that's what Jackson
has generally done in his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran John Salley, who played for Jackson in Chicago, said
before the game the Lakers were ''right where we're supposed to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   How did he know?
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been here before,'' Salley said. ''The way we practiced,
everybody took it to the utmost seriousness. They weren't tense,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   And did he expect to win?
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, yeah, I always expect to win,'' Salley said. ''I never
expect to lose. If I expected to lose, I'd have stayed home with a
virus, a hangnail.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a player coached by Phil Jackson, whose 114-43
record in playoff games (.726) is the best in NBA history. He may
have had the best players, and probably does now, but certainly
he's fulfilled his role.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers now face the Phoenix Suns in the Western Conference
semifinals, starting Sunday at Staples Center, where they've won 20
of their last 21 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0203 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
