<HEADLINE> Illegal D Calls Set Tone for Kings  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Following the Lakers' second defeat by
Sacramento, Los Angeles coach Phil Jackson claimed the Kings were
playing zone defense against Shaquille O'Neal without being called
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute into Friday night's fifth and deciding game
of their playoff series, the Lakers received an illegal defense
warning. Some two minutes later, the Kings were called twice in a
six-second span for being in an illegal defense, with the second
call a technical.
</P>
<P>
   That was the end of Sacramento defenders trying to sag back and
block the passing lane into the Lakers' big center, who scored 32
points and had seven of his rebounds on the offensive end of the
court.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers hit from outside, too, in their runaway 113-86
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''They (the referees) let us know they were here very quickly,''
Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said. ''I was very surprised the way
it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, they read the papers. If that's how it's going to
be, anybody who's going to play them (the Lakers) is in big
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Adelman quickly added, however, that the Lakers simply outplayed
his team.
</P>
<P>
   ''They controlled the tone of the game from the very start,'' he
said. ''They had us on our heels from the very start.
</P>
<P>
   ''We tried to get something going, but they wouldn't let us.
When they came out in the third quarter and ran it (the lead) to
25, that was pretty much it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings shot a miserable 34 percent, and Chris Webber, with 20
points, was their only player in double figures. Even he went
7-of-21 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just didn't play well,'' said Vlade Divac, who scored only
four points on 2-of-6 shooting against his former team. ''They are
a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's starting lineup had only 41 points -- to 45 by their
'Bench Mob' that was a key to the team's wins in the third and
fourth games.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, the underdog Kings rallied after
losing their first two games of the postseason. But unlike a year
earlier, when they extended Utah into overtime before losing Game
5, they were never really in the showdown against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disappointed we lost, but we'll get better,'' Divac
said. ''Next season, we need to play hard so we can have the
homecourt advantage for the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings haven't won a playoff series since 1981, when they
were still in Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
