<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: LAPD Faces Rights Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Justice Department officials will bring a
civil rights lawsuit against the Los Angeles Police Department
unless city officials agree to a number of reforms, the Los Angeles
Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-year probe that in recent months has focused more
on the department's Rampart station scandal, in which officers are
said to have framed, beat, robbed and shot innocent people, federal
investigators now believe they have enough evidence to sue the
LAPD, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office
served search warrants related to its Rampart probe at the homes of
17 Los Angeles police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rampart investigation has led to the dismissal of more than
80 convictions and the resignations, firings or suspensions of some
30 officers. Criminal charges have been filed against three
officers, and Police Chief Bernard Parks has said he expects more
people to be charged.
</P>
<P>
   Sources told the Times that Bill Lann Lee, the head of the
Justice Department's civil rights division, was to meet Monday
afternoon with a number of local officials, including the city
attorney, police chief and at least two City Council members.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has been monitoring the department since
1996 to determine whether it is guilty of a pattern of abusive
behavior. In recent months the probe has concentrated on the
Rampart scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Although it wasn't known what reforms officials might demand in
exchange for not suing, in previous cases they have insisted on the
appointment of an outside auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's searches were condemned by Ted Hunt, president of the
Los Angeles Police Protective League. He said prosecutors served
the warrants about 7 a.m. in front of officers' children and
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said the police union plans to go to court to challenge the
confiscation of notes from one officer's meetings with his attorney
and his defense representative.
</P>
<P>
   DA spokeswoman Victoria Pipkin said all 17 warrants were signed
by Superior Court Judge Larry Fidler. She refused to discuss
specific information about the warrants, which are sealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
