<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Party Hangs Over EU Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WIELAARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FURNAS, Azores (AP) -- The presence of the far-right Freedom
Party in Austria's government is casting a shadow over a meeting of
European Union foreign ministers gathered to debate European
security and EU enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel, a mainstream
conservative, increased pressure on his partners Friday to end
bilateral sanctions on cultural and sports exchanges imposed after
he formed a government with the Freedom Party on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Party has been embroiled in controversy since its
former leader, Joerg Haider, praised the ''orderly'' employment
policies of Nazi Germany and called Waffen SS veterans ''men of
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel's government issued an 18-point action plan to get the
sanctions dropped. If not, Austria will hold a referendum in the
fall in which voters could demand their fellow Europeans return to
business as usual. Such a referendum, although it will have largely
symbolic value, would be unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Neves, a spokesman for Portugal, which holds the EU
presidency, insisted that the sanctions are bilateral matters, not
an EU issue.
</P>
<P>
   That reasoning infuriates Austria, which argues that banning
cultural and sports exchanges may be mild measures but they pollute
the atmosphere at EU meetings when French, Belgian and other
delegates shun the usual group photo sessions. The sanctions also
fuel calls from Freedom Party officials for Austria to veto EU
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Vice Chancellor Susanne Riess-Passer, head of the
Freedom Party, said Friday that it ''was time to act'' to get
European nations to drop their bilateral measures.
</P>
<P>
   Before a referendum, Austria plans to conduct opinion polls with
EU citizens, send prominent Austrians in fields such as politics,
economics and culture to visit EU counties and have Schuessel visit
the EU executive commission in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers were to meet in a historic residence amid
gardens and natural springs on Sao Miguel, one of Portugal's Azores
islands.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda includes a debate about the Balkans and efforts to
revamp the EU's aid programs, which EU foreign and security policy
chief Javier Solana says are hobbled by red tape. Since 1991, the
EU and its member states have provided about $17 billion in aid to
Balkan nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Balkan debate will include a review of efforts to bring
lasting peace and reconciliation to Kosovo, where the NATO allies
have deployed 40,000 peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the ministers also will debate how to breathe new
life into discussions on overhauling the European Union's
convoluted decision-making rules. While all agree this is necessary
before the next round of enlargement in 2004 or thereabouts, the EU
governments are deadlocked in reform talks that began in February.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has said it also wants to discuss Zimbabwe, where mobs
and ruling party militants have occupied scores of farms in recent
days. By Friday, armed black squatters were camped on nearly 760
white-owned farms and had staked claims to a total of 1,190.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0228 </TRAILER>
