<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal O'Connor's Farewell Begins  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- During his 16 years in New York, Cardinal John
O'Connor was at the altar in St. Patrick's Cathedral for an
assortment of funerals and memorial services: for city heroes, for
New York Yankee great Joe DiMaggio, for the victims of TWA Flight
800 and Swissair Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   Now his chair sits empty, and it is O'Connor's time to be
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 mourners silently walked past his casket Friday
at the start of a four-day farewell to the cardinal, who died
Wednesday night at the age of 80. His body was returned Friday
afternoon to his beloved cathedral, arriving with a full police
escort.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was without a doubt the quintessential homebody,'' said
Bishop Patrick Sheridan, vicar general of St. Patrick's, during a
special rite observing O'Connor's final homecoming. ''His work is
done, and now he's home.''
</P>
<P>
   Organ music swelled and the church bells rang as the eight
pallbearers carried O'Connor's casket inside the cathedral. The
congregation sang a hymn, ''Now From the Heavens Descending,'' as
the pallbearers -- joined by a phalanx of priests, nuns and altar
servers -- slowly marched through the church.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-minute service marked O'Connor's return to the Manhattan
church he led for 16 years as the nation's highest-profile Roman
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   His dark wood coffin was carried through the ornate brass doors
of the Fifth Avenue church, then brought up the aisle and placed at
the front of the main altar.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is home now, in his beloved cathedral, the object of our
esteem,'' Sheridan said. ''May God grant him eternal rest.''
</P>
<P>
   A steady flow of mourners was soon marching past the open casket
to bid a final goodbye to the late spiritual leader of the
archdiocese's 2.4 million faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt inspired and touched,'' said Frank Zizzo of Levittown,
N.Y., whose wife Josephine visited the casket with him. ''He looked
incredibly at peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's body will lie in the cathedral all day Saturday
and Sunday. The funeral Mass was scheduled for Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, a special Mass was celebrated by the cardinal's
former secretary, Bishop James McCarthy of the St. Elizabeth Ann
Seton parish in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some have asked what will be his legacy,'' McCarthy said.
''May I suggest one: he saved lives -- the lives of the unborn, the
lives of the poor, the lives of those in war-torn nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the four-day farewell, O'Connor's body will remain at
St. Patrick's. The cardinal will be interred in the crypt beneath
the cathedral's altar, where all the previous archbishops of New
York are buried.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 0305 </TRAILER>
