<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year goes fast with hot primary contests for U.S. Senate  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- In no time, this year has become
politically hot in New Jersey, providing voters with contested,
closely fought primary races for U.S. Senate on both sides of the
political aisle.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks leading to June 6 were precipitated when U.S. Sen.
Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., decided early last year not to seek
re-election when his term expired at the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The contest became more complicated when his colleague, U.S.
Sen. Robert Torricelli, a chief national strategist for the
Democrats, recruited millionaire Jon Corzine, recently deposed as
chairman of Goldman Sachs, to run for Lautenberg's seat to keep it
in Democratic hands.
</P>
<P>
   And it turned topsy-turvy when the presumed front-runner for the
job, Republican Gov. Christie Whitman, decided last September to
bow out of the contest after talking about it and fueling GOP hopes
all summer.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for the Republican and Democratic nominations is wide
open, and the only political novice on the scene, Corzine, has
already shattered campaign spending records, so far deploying more
than $10 million just in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Following are thumbnail profiles of the six candidates.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   Jon Corzine
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, 53, of Summit, wants to win the campaign with
handshakes and personal charm. For good measure he is pouring
millions of dollars into TV commercials at a rate that may shatter
national records for spending in his effort to overcome a hostile,
well-known opponent and his own lack of name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   A former Wall Street financier with a fortune estimated at $300
million, Corzine is backed by the state Democratic Party and its
major leaders and county organizations, but he has fumbled some
under campaign pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Florio
</P>
<P>
   For Florio, 62, of Metuchen, this is a last chance to revive a
political career spanning four decades. Outspent and lagging in
party support, he is on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Florio tries to build mistrust of his wealthy opponent for a
cash-driven ''hostile takeover'' of the party while defending his
own decision as governor to raise taxes in 1990, from which his
party has yet to recover. Having run close in three statewide races
he has won or lost, Florio commands a loyal base of rank-and-file
Democrats, according to polls and pundits.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   Bob Franks
</P>
<P>
   Franks, 48, of Berkeley Heights, has spent seven years in the
U.S. House of Representatives emphasizing causes important to New
Jersey over those with partisan appeal or national import.
</P>
<P>
   A former state party chairman, Franks has won major county GOP
endorsements and hews to the traditional formula for Gov. Christie
Whitman and state Republicans, opposing taxes and government
spending, but moving center on abortion, gun control and campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gormley
</P>
<P>
   Long a prominent figure in the state Senate, Gormley, 54, of
Margate, has failed in previous campaigns for the GOP nomination
for governor and for Congress in the 2nd Congressional District. He
has since worked to broaden his record and his appeal, converting
hostility from pro-gun lobbies into a political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Many recognize a new, improved Gormley, including Donald Trump,
a one-time rival who is now raising money for him. Gormley is
expected to have a money edge, but strong efforts to win at least
one county endorsement north of Trenton failed.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Treffinger
</P>
<P>
   A son of Democrats, Treffinger, 49, of Verona, ventured into
bedrock Democratic territory to win two terms as Essex County
executive, making his career a case study in bureaucratic reform,
fiscal overhauls and political power-building. He calls on
Republicans to shed their image as the party of Wall Street and
become the ''party of the people,'' though he has had limited
success appealing to Republicans outside his Essex-Passaic base,
where he cuts into Franks' support.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Sabrin
</P>
<P>
   Sabrin, 53, of Leonia, was the Libertarian Party candidate for
New Jersey governor in 1997, but now shifts to the GOP, where his
anti-abortion views make a better fit. Seen as trailing the field,
the Ramapo College professor has shunned traditional party
organizations. He offers a neat picture of staunch conservatism,
opposing government regulation such as auto emissions tests,
opposing gun control and affirmative action. His Libertarian roots
explain his support for legalization of drugs and prostitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-06-00 1150 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
