<HEADLINE> Subpoenaed Notes Put on Web  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- The Wichita Eagle, found in contempt of
court for refusing to turn over a reporter's notes from his
interviews with a murder suspect, published them on its Internet
site before giving them to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle editor Rick Thames said, ''We reluctantly decided to
comply with the judge's order after ... determining that an appeal
would be difficult at best in this particular case.''
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick County District Judge Clark Owens found the newspaper
in contempt Tuesday after refusing its motion to quash a subpoena
for the notes and fining the paper $500 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Owens had said the notes should be turned over because they
contained material which was not available to prosecutors from any
other source.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves the March 27 killing of teacher Janice
Vredenburg, 52, at her Wichita home. Tanner Green, 23, is charged
with first-degree murder in her death.
</P>
<P>
   Green, a parolee who has refused to talk to police since being
accused of the crime, proclaimed his innocence in jailhouse
telephone interviews with reporter Tim Potter, giving a detailed
account of where he said he was on the day of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Potter's story on Green's comments was published April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, his notes, drafts and other unpublished material
relating to the Green interview were subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   Thames said The Eagle posted the reporter's notes Friday so the
newspaper could adhere to its policy of not releasing unpublished
information before handing them over to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In a column, Thames wrote: ''Many people with important things
to say would be less inclined to talk to The Eagle if they believed
the mere issuance of a subpoena could turn the newspaper into an
investigative arm of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''At the same time, reporters don't seek to impede
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The notes from Wichita Eagle reporter Tim Potter:
http://www.wichitaeagle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
