<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief D.C. Judge Hires GOP Lawyer  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chief federal judge in the District of
Columbia has hired prominent Republican attorney Michael Madigan to
represent her in a judicial misconduct investigation of why she
assigned campaign fund-raising cases and a Whitewater prosecution
to Clinton appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Legal sources at the courthouse said that in recent weeks before
Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson hired Madigan, she
summoned at least three clerk's office employees to her chambers
and questioned them about their recollections of the handling of
the cases.
</P>
<P>
   One employee was brought back for at least one additional round
of questioning by Johnson and all three employees were questioned
in the presence of a court reporter, said the sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A former assistant U.S. attorney in the District of Columbia
from 1969-73, Madigan was chief counsel for Sen. Fred Thompson's
campaign finance investigation of fund-raising abuses in the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've known the chief judge for a very long time and she is not
only one of the finest judges in the country, but one of the most
honorable people I have ever met,'' Madigan said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The clerical employees who were questioned by Johnson process
incoming case filings. Ordinarily, cases are assigned at random by
a computer system which the clerk's office administers.
</P>
<P>
   In the rare instances where a case is specially assigned by the
chief judge, the chief judge's office must have some contact with
employees in the clerk's office in order to direct a prosecution to
a particular judge.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson questioned the employees after a decision in early
February by the Judicial Council of appeals and district judges at
the courthouse to revive a complaint against Johnson that had been
filed last year by a conservative group, Judicial Watch. The
complaint was based on Johnson's assignment of two high-profile
prosecutions of presidential friends -- a tax evasion case against
Webster Hubbell and a campaign fund-raising case against former
Little Rock, Ark., restaurateur Charlie Trie.
</P>
<P>
   The Judicial Council reinstated the complaint after a Republican
congressman, Rep. Howard Coble of North Carolina, disclosed that
four additional cases involving alleged Democratic fund-raising
illegalities had been directed by Johnson to recent appointees of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Also working with Madigan in representing Johnson is former
House of Representatives legal counsel Steve Ross, a Democrat also
with the same firm as Madigan -- Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has rejected an invitation from Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind.,
to testify to the House Government Reform Committee on May 17 about
the special assignments in the high-profile cases.
</P>
<P>
   Burton spokesman Mark Corallo declined to comment, but according
to courthouse sources who have seen the letter signed by both
Madigan and Ross, the lawyers cite separation of powers between the
branches of government for her decision not to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, according to the legal sources, responded with a request
for information about any other cases that Johnson might have
assigned outside the computerized random selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Madigan, who was assistant minority counsel to the Senate
Watergate Committee, specializes in white-collar criminal defense
work, complex civil litigation and has represented officers and
directors of Fortune 500 companies in various congressional
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   He has served on the judicial nominating commission for judges
in the District of Columbia and the board of governors of the
District of Columbia Bar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
