<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House May Not Hold Elian Hearings  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Politics, public opinion and wariness about
past investigations are prompting House Republicans to skip
hearings into the Elian Gonzalez case, a turnabout for a party
whose other productions showcased Ruby Ridge, campaign finance and
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   There are dissenters, among them Reps. Bob Barr of Georgia and
John Doolittle of California. Both spoke up at a recent private
meeting to urge hearings into last month's predawn raid by armed
government agents who took the boy from the home of Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we've had a very egregious violation of fundamental
constitutional rights, and if we don't have hearings on this we're
going to give our stamp of approval,'' Doolittle said in a
subsequent interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Speaker Dennis Hastert, who initially wanted hearings ''into
the Clinton-Gore Justice Department's tactics and response'' in the
case, told fellow Republicans he no longer feels that way. Instead,
he is asking Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, to conduct an inquiry as the basis for a written report.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not planning hearings now,'' Hyde, R-Ill., said late last
week. ''I'm saying there could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar in the Senate, where GOP leaders backed
away from plans for full-fledged hearings after airing the issue
privately. Several sources, who declined to identified by name,
said word had been relayed to George W. Bush's presidential
campaign that there will be no high-profile effort that might turn
attention away from the party's principal goal, which is winning
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Hyde, Hastert, Barr and others are united in
expressing disgust at the Immigration and Naturalization Service
operation that reunited the boy with his father. Father and son
remain at a secluded retreat on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said at the closed meeting of the rank and file,
according to several participants, that he was horrified to see
pictures of armed INS agents take the boy. He considered the
episode un-American, the participants said.
</P>
<P>
   But other factors are at work.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a fierce election-year battle to hold the House,
many Republicans profess optimism about recent polling. Some argue
hearings would be a distraction from a core GOP message that
includes cutting taxes while protecting the Social Security
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we should be talking about is, 'We balanced the budget,
and we reformed welfare.' That's what we should be holding hearings
on,'' said Rep. James Walsh, a New Yorker who also spoke up at last
week's GOP caucus, or conference.
</P>
<P>
   Others note that polls indicate the public generally feels the
issue is essentially a custody fight, and 6-year-old Elian should
be with his father. Some Republicans said they fear hearings could
appear to place the GOP on the other side, particularly given the
strong feeling of many conservatives that nothing justifies sending
the boy back to Fidel Castro's communist Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ''I talked to a lot of people at home during the break, who told
me he should be with his father, and we ought to stay out of the
issue,'' said Rep. Howard McKeon, R-Calif., who spoke on the issue
at the weekly GOP whips meeting last week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ''We have not seemed to do very well at
hearings. ... I think that could be a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, top GOP aides made the same point more emphatically.
Republicans dealt awkwardly with extremist groups in the Ruby Ridge
hearings, in the view of some Republicans. That case dealt with the
death of white separatist Randy Weaver's wife at the hands of an
FBI sharpshooter in the 1992 siege in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance hearings into allegations of wrongdoing by
President Clinton turned into a political brawl as Democats sought
to tarnish the effort. Dissatisfied with conduct of the probe,
then-Speaker Newt Gingrich insisted on dismissal of a top aide to
Rep. Dan Burton, the Indiana Republican who led the investigating
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment hearings 18 months ago became highly partisan as
Democrats labored to depict Republicans as political extremists
determined to overturn a national election.
</P>
<P>
   ''The administration has proven themselves to be very adept at
obfuscating and stonewalling and turning hearings into circuses,''
said Ed Gillespie, a former aide to Majority leader Dick Armey and
communications director at the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''And even though it's the administration that's the clowns,
it's the (Republican-controlled) Congress that gets the fallout.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats reject Gillespie's characterization of them but share
the broader point. Several aides interviewed last week saw hearings
as a potential political plus for the Democrats and expressed hope
the Republicans would plunge ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans who feel that way are in the minority among
their peers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Too many people are paying too much attention to polls and are
more interested in responding to polls than they are to actually
leading the nation,'' Barr said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The case ''has nothing to do with the issues of custody per se.
It has to do with whether the Department of Justice abides by the
same rule of law'' as the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- David Espo is chief congressional correspondent
for The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
