<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Governor Endorses China Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If U.S. business doesn't get a crack at
selling American cars, food and manufactured goods to China's 1.2
billion consumers, companies in other countries surely will,
Tennessee Gov. Don Sundquist argued Saturday in the Republicans'
weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should agree to permanent normal trade relations with
China to ensure that Americans gain business opportunities in ''the
world's biggest and most important emerging market,'' Sundquist
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last fall, China agreed to unilaterally open its markets to
other nations, including the United States, and to play by
international rules of trade. The only question now is whether the
Chinese buy from the U.S. or from another country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a popular view among state governors, 43 of whom signed a
letter to House and Senate leaders last week in support of
permanent normal trade with China. President Clinton is leading the
drive to normalize trade.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would give China the same permanent low-tariff
access to American markets now routinely extended to almost every
U.S. trading partner. China's status currently must be renewed
every year.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also would ease China's entry into the World
Trade Organization, the Geneva-based organization that sets the
rules for world trade. China will have the conditions negotiated
with the United States even if the legislation is rejected, but
benefits for U.S. traders would be denied.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing congressional objections, the Clinton administration
has said it will work to ensure that China lives up to its promises
to further open its markets if Congress votes for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A House vote is expected in two weeks. If it passes, the Senate
likely would take it up next month.
</P>
<P>
   Sundquist admitted that China must improve its human rights
record, but he said Republican governors believe trade and
communication with China will put China ''on the path to a more
democratic society.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Developing China's private sector through commerce and trade
is the best way to free the Chinese people from government control
and ensure their continued exposure to freedom,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
