<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New budget, same old way of deciding the toughest issues  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- As much as legislative leaders kept
stressing the words ''open'' and ''in public'' when discussing how
the 2000-01 state budget was negotiated, the most important issues
were again settled in closed-door bargaining sessions among the
leaders and Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Year Three of the use of budget conference committees by the
Legislature saw lawmakers continuing to give more credit to the
committee process than it deserved, based on key provisions of the
final budget the committees had nothing to do with.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and Pataki committed to spend about $77.5 billion for
the year beginning April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the nine conference committees of Assembly and Senate
members which met between April 5-17 decided how to spend ''only''
about $1 billion. And the parameters of their spending was in most
cases set in advance by the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the legislative leaders and Pataki made deals
among themselves on $1.5 billion worth of tax cuts; on presenting a
$3.8 billion transportation bond act to voters this November; on a
$34.2 billion, five-year capital plan for transportation and mass
transit; on a record $1.2 billion aid increase for public schools;
on a debt-reform initiative, to mention only a few examples.
</P>
<P>
   This came after private negotiations among the legislative
leaders and Pataki in December produced a new deal on New York's $9
billion health care financing system, including a new health
insurance program for up to 1 million working poor New Yorkers and
a near doubling of the state's cigarette tax to a
highest-in-the-nation $1.11 a pack.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric to the contrary, Albany remained a place during the
2000 budget negotiations where an extraordinary amount of power is
concentrated in the hands of the governor, the speaker of the state
Assembly and the majority leader of the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the risk of stating the obvious, the budget process is
still in great need of reform,'' said Martin Connor, who is leader
of the Senate's Democratic minority.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year the budget negotiation process in some small way
took on the look of being open to the public. But as soon as the
ship hit the shoals, it was up to the three leaders -- and not
rank-and-file members of the Legislature -- to patch the leaks.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's budget was approved on May 5; last year, the impasse
went on until Aug. 4. From the standpoint of timing, the
legislative leaders and governor weren't nearly as bad in 2000 as
they have been in some past years.
</P>
<P>
   But they never came close to reversing what is now a
16-year-long skein of failing to pass a timely budget.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno insisted repeatedly in March
and April that he would not be involved in old-style
''three-men-in-a-room'' budget negotiating sessions with Pataki and
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver over the 2000-01 budget. Yet
participate he did, and after the budget was passed he sounded
resigned about the necessity of such closed-door bargaining, at
least late in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''We keep trying to keep the process public and we went with the
conference committees and it's about as public, I guess, as it can
be when you're preparing to wind things up and close,'' he said.
''It's apparent that some discussion must take place (in private)
as they take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said making deals on the most significant budget issues
is what there are leaders for.
</P>
<P>
   ''Debt reform is an issue that took place between leaders,'' he
said. ''Cleaning up transportation, cleaning up various things that
the subcommittees did is the job of leadership. I think it was a
good mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Silver and Bruno said rank-and-file legislators were
satisfied they were involved in the budget process in a significant
way. Silver said if the reports of the nine subcommittees were
''lined up'' with spending in the final budget, the subcommittee
recommendations were closely followed.
</P>
<P>
   Closely, but not religiously if it did not fit into the leaders'
designs.
</P>
<P>
   The health conference committee recommended an Oct. 1 start date
for an expansion of the EPIC prescription drug program for senior
citizens, for example. When the final version of the budget
emerged, ''leadership'' had been pushed back to Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   And Pataki's shadow hung over the conference committee process,
or, rather, the prospect of him making wholesale vetoes to the
budget the Legislature sent him. Legislative leaders needed to know
if some spending in this year's budget would similarly face vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process required that some of the process be done with the
governor and therefore not be done at the public conference
committees,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko first covered the adoption of a New York state
budget in 1981. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol
Station, Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
