<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rochester author wins prestigious mystery writers award  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- ''Never Trust a Dead Man,'' by Rochester
author Vivian Vande Velde, has been named best novel for young
adults in 1999 by the Mystery Writers of America.
</P>
<P>
   It tells the humorous tale of a 17-year-old boy who is wrongly
accused of killing a romantic rival and gets imprisoned inside a
cave with the corpse. With a witch's help, the dead man comes back
to life as a bat and teams up with the boy to hunt for the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a medieval fantasy world, Vande Velde's 17th book
produced her first major literary prize at the Mystery Writers'
annual Edgar Allan Poe Awards dinner in New York on Thursday night.
''I am still about two inches from the ceiling,'' Vande Velde said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Her first mystery story -- ''the rest have been more fantasy or
adventure'' -- is spiced with the wry humor that runs through all
her works. ''I'm afraid I don't take too much seriously,'' she
said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   After working a variety of secretarial jobs in the 1970s, Vande
Velde began writing around the time her daughter was born 21 years
ago. The key to success? ''I think a good writer has to love
stories -- you can't fake it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Vande Velde, 48, now averages two books a year, and the
trickiest part is deciding what to write about. ''Once I get the
idea, then it comes very quickly. ... All of those possibilities in
the world, it's hard for me to focus,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her next suspense mystery, ''Magic Can Be Murder,'' will be
published by Harcourt Brace in the fall and her first non-fantasy,
tentatively titled ''Alison, Who Went Away,'' is due out next year.
Vande Velde also has written books for younger children and for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The Edgar awards are named for the father of the modern mystery
story. Previous winners include Alfred Hitchcock and Mickey
Spillane.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Burke of Los Alamitos, Calif., won the Edgar for best
mystery fiction book in 1999 for ''Bones,'' Eliot Pattison got top
honors for best first American novel for ''The Skull Mantra,'' and
James B. Stewart's ''Blind Eye'' won as best fact crime book.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1946, Mystery Writers of America is an organization
dedicated to promoting the genre. It represents more than 3,000
writers, editors, agents, booksellers, librarians and others with
an interest in mystery writing.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are no cash prizes, honored books often go into
additional printings. ''An Edgar can make a career,'' said the
organization's spokeswoman, Sherry Zannoth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-06-00 1349 </TRAILER>
