<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commencement Season Underway  </HEADLINE>
By ARLENE LEVINSON, AP National Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The words were the same as those echoing through the auditoriums
of hundreds of universities, but the venue was anything but
conventional as Jones International University President Pamela
Pease, clad in a cap and gown and framed by a virtual stone arch,
held up a diploma before a camera in Denver and conferred eight
degrees online.
</P>
<P>
   At Michigan State University the same day, a handful of
graduates turned their backs on the stage and walked out in protest
as a chorus of boos greeted commencement speaker James Wolfensohn,
president of the beleaguered World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, college dropout Drew Carey was drafting the 15
minutes of insight he'd deliver Sunday at his hometown's Cleveland
State University.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not going to be serious,'' Carey promised by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   This is the season of mortarboards, memories and many, many
speeches -- most inoffensive and inspirational, some sparking
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Being an election year, the speaker circuit is thick with
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has already addressed graduates of Eastern
Michigan University. He'll be at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy in
New London, Conn., on May 17 and Carleton College in Northfield,
Minn., June 10. Vice President Al Gore speaks at Columbia
University Law School May 16 and at West Point May 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family could use its own speaker's bureau. Former first
lady Barbara Bush appeared Saturday at Centenary College of
Louisiana. Her husband, former president George Bush, has three
bookings: Rice University in Houston on May 13, Monmouth College in
Illinois on May 14, and St. Anselm College in New Hampshire on May
20.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the Texas governor and presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, addresses graduates at Prairie View A&AMP;M
University in Texas on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   The field is also dotted with celebrities, some unaccustomed to
the propriety of caps and gowns, others strangers to the
controversy they can arouse among students.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Rogers of ''Mister Rogers Neighborhood'' is a perennial
favorite. Last year, graduates at Marist College in Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., joined him in singing his theme, ''It's a Beautiful Day in
the Neighborhood.'' But when Old Dominion University in Norfolk,
Va., wooed him for commencement this Saturday, some students
balked, saying they were too grown up for the patriarch of PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Don Marshall, a 46-year-old Navy veteran receiving a bachelor's
degree in business computers, said he planned to boycott Rogers'
speech, adding, ''He's not the appropriate speaker for our age
group.''
</P>
<P>
   John Broderick, vice president of institutional advancement at
Old Dominion, shrugged off the complaints. ''A college campus is
really a marketplace of ideas,'' he said. ''That's what choosing a
commencement speaker is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Rogers got a standing ovation from the 2,100
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know you don't have to do anything sensational in order to
love or be loved,'' Rogers told the students, many of whom grew up
watching his show. ''What ultimately nourishes us is knowing we can
be trusted, that the foundation of our being is good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Students at Antioch College in Yellow Springs, Ohio, drew
hundreds of protesters to campus when they picked a condemned
killer.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking via videotape from death row April 29, Mumia Abu-Jamal
insisted he was innocent of the murder for which he was jailed,
that of a Philadelphia police officer. The officer's wife and
off-duty police joined others outside in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle of Higher Education Almanac estimates that 2.2
million degrees, associate level to doctorate, will be conferred by
more than 4,000 institutions this spring.
</P>
<P>
   While only a few of those degrees will be presented online the
way Jones International University's were, more graduation
ceremonies are appearing on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Lesley College in Cambridge, Mass., is building a special Web
site to share its May 22 ceremonies with farflung masters graduates
of the school's technology in education program. The University of
Connecticut plans to put its May 21 graduation online so families
of 700 foreign graduate students can stay home.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Graduation archived at Jones International University:
http://graduation.jonesinternational.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
