<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., L.A. Officials Meet Over LAPD  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Justice Department officials are to meet
Monday with Los Angeles authorities to work on a settlement of the
department's long-running investigation into whether city police
have engaged in racial discrimination, a government official said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Assistant Attorney General Bill Lann Lee, head of the
department's civil rights division, and several other officials
will travel to Los Angeles for the meeting, Justice spokesman Myron
Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin said the meeting will be to discuss the investigation. He
refused to go into details, ''because it's a pending matter.''
</P>
<P>
   A government official, who requested anonymity, said the goal is
to negotiate a settlement. It would include revisions in police
training and procedures to end the pattern and practice of racial
discrimination that Justice investigators have found in the Los
Angeles Police Department, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Justice investigation, the official said, Lee has
been authorized to file a civil lawsuit against the city to obtain
the revisions, should the negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
   The developments come amid the police department's Rampart
station scandal, in which officers are said to have framed, beaten,
robbed and shot innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office
served search warrants related to its Rampart probe at the homes of
17 Los Angeles police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rampart investigation has led courts to overturn more than
80 convictions and to the resignations, firings or suspensions of
some 30 officers. Criminal charges have been filed against three
officers, and Police Chief Bernard Parks has said he expects more
people to be charged.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has been monitoring the LAPD since 1996
to determine whether it shows a pattern of abusive behavior. In
recent months the investigation has concentrated on the Rampart
scandal, according to the Los Angeles Times, which published
Saturday the first report of Monday's planned meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hunt, president of the Los Angeles Police Protective League,
condemned Friday's searches. He said prosecutors served the
warrants about 7 a.m. in front of officers' children and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said the police union plans to go to court to challenge
confiscation of notes from one officer's meetings with his attorney
and his defense representative.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Pipkin, a spokeswoman for the Los Angeles district
attorney, said all 17 warrants were signed by Superior Court Judge
Larry Fidler. She refused to discuss specific information about the
warrants, which are sealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
