<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Peace Timeline  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Key recent developments in Northern Ireland's
struggle for
peace:
<TEXT>
<P>
   1993
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 15: British and Irish governments offer IRA-linked Sinn
Fein party a place in negotiations if Irish Republican Army first
renounces violence. Britain suggests this should involve the
surrender of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   1994
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 1: IRA begins what it calls ''complete cessation of
military operations.'' British seek assurances IRA's truce will be
permanent and a commitment to eventual disarmament. Neither are
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 13: Two major outlawed pro-British groups, the Ulster
Defense Association and Ulster Volunteer Force, call joint
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   1995
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 28: On eve of President Clinton's first trip to Northern
Ireland, British and Irish governments appoint former U.S. Sen.
George Mitchell to resolve IRA disarmament controversy.
</P>
<P>
   1996
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 23: Mitchell proposes that IRA gradually disarm during
course of future multiparty talks involving Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 9: IRA ends cease-fire, kills two men with one-ton truck
bomb in London.
</P>
<P>
   June 10: Multiparty talks chaired by Mitchell open in Belfast.
Sinn Fein barred.
</P>
<P>
   1997
</P>
<P>
   May 16: New British Prime Minister Tony Blair promises Sinn Fein
place in talks if IRA calls new truce.
</P>
<P>
   July 20: IRA renews cease-fire. Two hard-line Protestant parties
boycott talks as Sinn Fein walks in.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 27: Assassination of senior Protestant militant ''King
Rat'' triggers wave of gun attacks on Catholics; paramilitary
cease-fires in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   1998
</P>
<P>
   March 25: Mitchell sets April 9 as agreement deadline.
</P>
<P>
   April 10, Good Friday: Eight parties accept an accord
envisioning a Protestant-Catholic administration, links with the
Irish Republic, gradual paroles for IRA and pro-British convicts
and disarmament of paramilitary groups to be completed on May 22,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   May 22: Voters approve accord in Northern Ireland and Irish
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   July 1: David Trimble, Protestant leader of the Ulster Unionist
Party, elected future senior Cabinet minister. Says Sinn Fein won't
get Cabinet posts unless IRA starts to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 15: Dissident IRA car bomb kills 29 people in Omagh,
deadliest terrorist strike in Northern Irish history.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16: Trimble and John Hume, moderate Catholic leader of
Social Democratic and Labor Party, win Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31: De-facto deadline for appointing new Cabinet passes
without agreement.
</P>
<P>
   1999
</P>
<P>
   May 15: After IRA refuses to make disarmament commitment, Blair
announces ''absolute deadline'' of June 30 for resolution.
</P>
<P>
   July 2: Blair unveils ''way forward'' document proposing that
IRA disarmament commence days after Cabinet's formation. Trimble
rejects it.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 6: Mitchell opens review into why Good Friday accord is
gridlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 18: Mitchell brokers plan that requires Ulster Unionists to
accept Sinn Fein in Cabinet, Sinn Fein to pledge disarmament is
''essential'' and the IRA to start cooperating with disarmament
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 2: Ulster Unionists, Social Democratic and Labor Party and
Sinn Fein sit down around same Cabinet table; fourth coalition
member, Democratic Unionists, boycotts meeting but accepts posts.
</P>
<P>
   2000
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 31: Disarmament commission says IRA has made no move to
give up arms.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 11: With the Ulster Unionists about to withdraw from
Cabinet, British resume direct rule. A last-minute IRA offer on
disarmament is deemed too vague to prevent suspension of
power-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   May 5: After intense negotiations involving Ulster Unionists and
Sinn Fein, Britain and Ireland call for power-sharing to resume May
22 and for the disarmament deadline to be extended to June 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1447 </TRAILER>
