<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Moving Slowly in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian military's slow pace against Chechen
rebels in recent weeks was gauged to prevent casualties, Russia's
defense minister said Saturday, promising the insurgents would
eventually be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said the lives of federal
soldiers are more important than a quick victory. ''The main thing
is, don't hurry us, so we don't lose our own people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev's comments may have been aimed at shoring up popular
support for the Chechen conflict. Initially a large majority of
Russians backed the military campaign, but public support has
appeared less certain in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops quickly seized two-thirds of Chechnya after
invading the breakaway republic last September. But they have had
far less success fighting the rebels in the republic's southern
mountains, and leaders of the militants say they have no intention
of surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have inflicted heavy casualties on troop convoys in
ambushes recently, defying claims that they are on the run or
incapable of posing a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of rebels kept up their hit-and-run attacks late
Friday and Saturday, shooting at federal forces across Chechnya,
according to the federal press center in the Caucasus. There were
no reports of Russian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military was bolstering defenses throughout Chechnya
on Saturday in preparation for the May 9 celebrations of the defeat
of Nazi Germany in World Ward II. Commanders have said they expect
the rebels to try to mar the anniversary with attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see that their preparation is increasing, how they're
preparing various plans, including seizing towns,'' Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a Russian official said up to 5,500 Chechen males
could be drafted into the army. All Russian men aged 18-27 are
eligible for the draft, but conscription has not been enforced in
Chechnya because the region was under the control of a rebel
government.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting Chechen men could restore public faith in Russian
forces after years of rebel rule and months of devastating military
conflict, said Alexander Petrov, Russia's military commissioner in
Chechnya. He said any conscripted Chechens would probably be posted
inside the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Conscription would likely be deeply unpopular in the republic.
Many residents deeply distrust the Russian military.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1449 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Said To Tighten Media Control  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Chinese authorities have stopped issuing
tourist visas to foreign journalists in a bid to tighten controls
on media, a newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign journalists can now make personal trips to mainland
China only as part of government-supervised tour groups, a foreign
ministry spokeswoman in Hong Kong was quoted as telling the South
China Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong Journalists Association called the controls
''unreasonable,'' saying they ''infringe on freedom of movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The move reverses a decade-old policy of usually allowing Hong
Kong and foreign journalists to travel freely in the mainland when
not working, the English-language daily reported. Journalist visas
are required to do reporting work, although the Chinese authorities
haven't always enforced the rule.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said the visa restrictions coincide with
government campaigns to purge liberal Chinese academics and
restrain foreign correspondents in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the mainland authorities recently
quietly changed the visa rules, and several Hong Kong-based foreign
journalists have already been denied access tourist visas in the
past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The controls do not apply to Hong Kong Chinese journalists who
travel to China using home visit permits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1451 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Mayor Gets Call From Blair  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Ken Livingstone began his first full day as
London's newly elected mayor Saturday talking by phone to Prime
Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who had warned before Livingstone's election victory that
the maverick lawmaker ''would be a disaster,'' phoned Livingstone
at Romney House, which is serving as temporary headquarters for the
new London government. It was the first time the two men had spoken
since Livingstone was declared the winner Friday of the first
citywide mayoral race.
</P>
<P>
   They talked for 20 minutes, and their conversation was described
by Blair's Labor Party as ''very positive and constructive.''
Livingstone said later that it was ''friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone was kicked out of the Labor Party after deciding to
run as an independent candidate against the prime minister's
preferred choice.
</P>
<P>
   During the often bitter campaign, Blair had warned Londoners not
to vote for Livingstone. He said Friday after the votes were
tallied that his views had not changed, but that he was determined
to cooperate with the new mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone, dressed casually in jeans for his first day in the
office, also promised to work with Blair.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not worried about what people think about me, but I am
worried about what they can do for London,'' said Livingstone, who
invited some Labor Party members on Saturday to hold key posts in
his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't ask people to love me. I'm not asking them to spend a
week on holiday with me. But can we get a bit more money to solve
London's problems?''
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who also celebrated his 47th birthday on Saturday,
created the mayoral job as part of his program of building up
regional government.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor, Livingstone will serve as an ambassador for the
capital's 7.25 million residents, oversee a $5.3 billion budget and
assume responsibility for the police, transportation, fire and
emergency services. He must also work with the newly elected
25-member London Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
