</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Immigration Officers Probed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thai immigration police will
investigate whether their fellow officers aided traffickers who
used a two-year-old Thai boy to try to smuggle a Chinese woman into
the United States, an investigator said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Police Capt. Suphamitr Katasila said police will look into how
the woman obtained a Thai immigration stamp found in her fake
Singaporean passport.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will call some immigration officers at the Bangkok Airport
for questioning,'' he said. ''We cannot help having a suspicion
that some officers might have a part in this illegal business.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 11, the toddler, the Chinese woman and a man flew into
Los Angeles. The toddler was given a fake name, and the man and
woman claimed to be his parents. They were deported after an
inspector discovered their fraudulent passports, but the boy was
kept in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities believe the boy was used as a prop to bolster
the impression the group was a family on vacation. Suspicion that
his natural mother was in on the scheme has caused his return to
Thailand to be delayed while the issue of custody is debated.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese woman, identified as Sue Mei Long, 22, is free on
bail from a Thai court and is expected to report to court officials
on May 15. She will be tried in Thailand before being sent home,
Suphamitr said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have already deported the man in the scheme, identified
as Suseno Karjorpanoto of Indonesia. He was given a suspended
six-month-jail term for making and using a fake passport.
</P>
<P>
   Suphamitr said police cannot investigate whether the boy's
mother was involved in the smuggling scheme unless someone files a
complaint against her.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has so far denied the allegation that she had a part in
it,'' he said. ''She did not know where her Indonesian friend had
taken the boy to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1452 </TRAILER>
