<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki administration reports index crime down 7 percent  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Thanks mainly to a fall-off in rapes,
burglaries and motor vehicle thefts, serious crime was down by
nearly 7 percent in New York state in 1999, the Pataki
administration reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The state Division for Criminal Justice Services' statistics
were based on reports of crimes to local law enforcement agencies
in the state. State officials said the numbers could change
''slightly'' when final crime statistics for 1999 are released by
the agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the 603,841 serious crimes reported last year in New
York were down 6.9 percent from 1998 numbers. Pataki, who got
elected in 1994 against Democrat Mario Cuomo in part by running as
a law-and-order candidate, said serious crimes have dropped by 34.3
percent since he was elected. There were 919,210 serious crimes
reported to police in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also ran in 1994 on a tax-cutting platform, and he said
the success of lowering taxes is reflected in the crime statistics,
as are anti-crime measures during his administration such as ending
parole for violent felons and DNA technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''These initiatives, combined with an improved economy spurred
in part by our unprecedented tax cuts, are making our streets and
neighborhoods safer than they've been in a generation,'' he said in
a statement released by his office Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest statistics involve ''index'' crimes, which are among
the most serious offenses. They showed reported rapes down 13.3
percent, from 3,836 to 3,326, in 1998; burglaries were down 12.2
percent, from 103,923 to 91,244; motor vehicle thefts fell 9
percent, from 67,665 to 61,575; robberies fell just under 9
percent, from 49,218 to 44,838; aggravated assaults fell 7 percent,
from 61,842 to 57,513; larcenies fell 4.4 percent, from 361,210 to
345,317; property crimes dropped 6.6 percent, from 532,798 to
497,633 and murders were down less than 1 percent, from 922 to 917.
</P>
<P>
   The New York statistics mirror the latest round of FBI
statistics for crime nationally. That data, released in November
1999, showed reports of index crimes to police agencies in the
first six months of last year declined 10 percent. The national
numbers showed reports of murders (down 13 percent), burglaries
(down 14 percent) and auto thefts (12 percent) were the crime
categories with the biggest drops.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, FBI statistics showed a 7.3 percent drop in index
crimes and declines each year going back to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki used release of the latest New York statistics to push
for various anti-crime bills he favors in the state Legislature,
including expansion of the state's DNA database for all offenders,
ending parole for people convicted of non-violent felonies, and
toughening laws against domestic violence and reforming sex assault
laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
