<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Applauds Ireland Move  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The decision by the Irish Republican Army to
begin disarming is ''a truly historic step,'' President Clinton
said. Saturday, he said, was ''a very good day for the people of
Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   ''For the first time the IRA is clearly committed to
decommissioning and a process to get there. I applaud that,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The outlawed IRA gave its commitment a day after the British and
Irish governments announced ambitious plans to transfer power back
to the province's suspended Catholic-Protestant administration on
May 22 and to extend the deadline for total IRA disarmament from
that day to June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very good day for the people of Northern Ireland. It
is a truly historic step,'' Clinton said before leaving the White
House for Andrews Air Force Base and a flight to his home state
Arkansas. ''I hope it will be fully accepted by all parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he believes the agreement will stick this time.
''We never got this far on the details of implementation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Republican Army struggled for close to three decades
to end British sovereignty over the six counties of Northern
Ireland and unite them with Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in December, a coalition Cabinet was formed to give the
province a measure of local control. The Cabinet was first proposed
as part of the U.S.-mediated Good Friday peace accord of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA did not announce by February it was laying down its
arms, however, and Britain reimposed direct rule. The Cabinet was
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke on the White House lawn near a waiting helicopter.
He was to spend the weekend in Arkansas, where he is to speak
Sunday at a Little Rock fund-raiser for first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Senate campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier written statement, the president said he welcomed
the IRA's commitment to put arms ''beyond use'' and the its
agreement to allow international inspectors into its arms dumps.
</P>
<P>
   ''These developments offer renewed hope to the people of
Northern Ireland that politics will once and for all be pursued
through exclusively political means,'' Clinton said. ''The United
States remains ready to assist this process in any way we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
