<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Accuses Eritrea on Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ABEBE ANDUALEM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Ethiopia's foreign minister accused
Eritrea on Saturday of derailing talks aimed at resolving their
23-month border dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Seyoum Mesfin said the indirect discussions -- or ''proximity
talks'' -- in Algeria's capital, Algiers, broke down after Eritrea
set preconditions. He spoke ominously of evaporating hopes for
peace in a sporadic two-year border conflict that has already left
tens of thousands of soldiers and civilians dead.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have now reached a critical period when prospects for a
peaceful resolution of the conflict have been blocked by Eritrea,''
Seyoum told reporters in the Ethiopian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Both Eritrea and Ethiopia have accepted a framework peace
agreement and a broad implementation strategy drafted by the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia, however, has questioned the technical arrangements for
implementing the accord, particularly the possibility that
peacekeepers would be stationed in contested areas along the
disputed 620-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   At the talks, which ended in deadlock Thursday after four days,
Seyoum said Eritrea demanded the two sides sign the framework
agreement, the implementation strategy and a cease-fire accord as a
prerequisite for any substantive discussions. Ethiopia rejected the
demands.
</P>
<P>
   European Union special envoy Reno Serri, U.S. special envoy
Anthony Lake and U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for Africa Susan
Rice traveled to Algiers to encourage a settlement but failed,
Seyoum said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Eritrean delegation did not go to Algiers to make peace
but to scuttle the peace prospects,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two Horn of Africa countries went to war in May 1998 over
their frontier, which has not been demarcated since Eritrea gained
independence from Ethiopia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   This week's talks were held under the supervision of Algerian
Justice Minister Ahmed Ouyahia, the personal representative of
Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
