<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nev. 'Quickie Divorce' Home Marked  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT SONNER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- There are churches, courthouses, breweries and
even casinos on the National Register of Historic Places. And now
there's also a house recognized for its role in the making of the
''quickie divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nystrom Guest House was one of the most famous homes away
from home for people trying to establish the minimum six-week
residency to obtain a divorce in Nevada in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other states and territories were lengthening the period of
residence, trying to make it harder to get a divorce, the
presumption being there would be fewer breakups of families,''
state archivist Guy Rocha said. ''People were coming to Reno
because it was the last venue in the country with a six-month
divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers saw an opportunity in the making.
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, they cut Nevada's residency requirement to three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then, after the Great Depression they decided that they were
attracting so many people, that if they made it even easier to get
divorced, maybe even more people would come to Reno,'' said Mella
Harmon, a historic preservation specialist for the state.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1931, the residency period went to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It had its desired effect. It was a great economic strategy
during the Depression,'' Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 32,000 divorces were granted in Washoe County from
1929 to 1939, a time when Reno's population totaled about 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1930s, the county was averaging 5,000 divorces a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Many divorcees spent their time waiting at the Nystrom House, a
few blocks west of downtown near the Sands Regency Hotel Casino.
</P>
<P>
   The original Gothic, wood-siding house, now covered in stucco,
was built in 1875 as the home of Washoe County Clerk J.S.
Shoemaker. It changed hands several times and was purchased during
World War II by Victor and Estelle Nystrom, who moved from San
Francisco to take part in the divorce trade. Mrs. Nystrom ran the
boarding house from the early 1940s until she died in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While Reno's divorce trade has become mostly a thing of the past
since other states began liberalizing their divorce laws in the
1960s, the folklore lives on, especially tales of newly divorced
women throwing their wedding rings into the Truckee River, which
runs through downtown Reno a block from the Washoe County
Courthouse. Some versions of the tale describe fishermen catching
trout in the river with rings in their bellies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some say it is a myth. Some say it is true,'' said Harmon, who
works for the State Historic Preservation Office under the Nevada
Department of Museums, Library and Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those things probably happened but less frequently than
portrayed. It may have been enhanced by the telling. It was the
Depression. Who was going to throw away a wedding ring?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rocha, the state archivist, believes there's some truth to the
ring tales.
</P>
<P>
   Salvage divers over the years, he said, have recovered ''all
sorts of things from the river, including rings.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Reno/Sparks Convention and Visitors Authority:
http://www.playreno.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
