<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Game jackpot rolls over to record $300 million  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID PITT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- How much bigger can the Big Game get?
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows after players failed to choose all six
numbers drawn Friday in the Big Game, swelling the jackpot to more
than $300 million -- the largest in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   The jackpot tops the previous largest lottery prize of $295.7
million two years ago in the Powerball game, won by 13 machinists
from Westerville, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we're in uncharted water,'' Virginia Lottery executive
director Penelope Kyle said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 122 million tickets were sold from 11 p.m. Tuesday to
11 p.m. Friday in the seven Big Game states, exceeding estimates of
118 million on which Friday's jackpot of $230 million was based.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Lottery Corp. President Rebecca Paul said she was among
many surprised by the Big Game's sheer bigness.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had anticipated the jackpot would approach $200 million,
but we never thought it would go over $200 (million), much less
$300 million,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic ticket sales drove Friday night's jackpot higher than
the estimated $230 million.
</P>
<P>
   And lottery officials said Saturday it would be difficult to
gauge the jackpot for Tuesday's drawing, which might be raised
after officials confer Monday morning. Directors of the seven Big
Game states -- Georgia, Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan,
New Jersey and Virginia -- have a daily telephone conference about
the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Game hit $197 million last year, its previous highest
pot.
</P>
<P>
   However, New Jersey had not yet joined, so it is difficult to
factor the impact nearby New York gamblers will have, Kyle said.
</P>
<P>
   For Friday's game, New Jersey sold the most tickets -- 33.95
million, attributed to the huge populations in adjacent New York
City and Philadelphia. Georgia and Illinois sold just over 21
million tickets each. Maryland sold the least, 7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three players were one number shy, collecting $150,000
each.
</P>
<P>
   Even lottery directors were amazed no one won after they saw the
numbers -- 6-8-16-30-32 and a Big Money Ball of 26.
</P>
<P>
   Sales records showed that 70 to 75 percent of the possible
combinations had been covered, officials said, and low numbers
often indicate that someone will hit the jackpot because many
players use anniversary dates or birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   ''We watched the drawing and they were all low numbers and we
thought we'd have about 10 winners,'' Kyle said. ''These were
winnable numbers, not bizarre numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another frenzy is expected as people contemplate $300 million up
for grabs Tuesday night. Lottery officials said they're prepared.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, lottery employees will help retailers manage the
crunch at the state's 10 to 15 largest sellers, Kyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery traffic in many locations picked up early Saturday as
players checked their tickets and realized they didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Miller, 48, of Chicago, said he will buy a ticket even
though he usually doesn't. And he noted there is no such thing as a
jackpot that is too big.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is America, land of capitalism,'' Miller said. ''There's
no such thing as too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Serv-U-Well Party Shoppe in Detroit, manager Nash Kassab
said players get creative when picking numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got some people who take them out of the garbage and play
other people's numbers,'' Kassab said. But it has been good for
business.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's people coming in that I've never seen before, that
have never played the lottery,'' Kassab said. ''Everybody hopes to
win the 300 million, nobody comes in to win a dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday will bring a winner, Kyle predicts. And she expects more
than one.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have so many people playing across the country,'' she said.
''People can fantasize about the $300 million, but I believe there
will be several matching tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ''This thing's not going on any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Big Game results: http://www.theofficialbiggame.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
