<HEADLINE> Prost! New Jersey homebrewers unite for Big Brew 2000  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF LINKOUS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TURNERSVILLE, N.J. (AP) -- It was a day more suited for relaxing
and swigging a glass of beer, but on Saturday beer enthusiasts from
southern New Jersey and Princeton had a better idea.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to make beer as well.
</P>
<P>
   From a parking lot in a strip mall off busy Route 42, about 40
brewers -- including many members of the Gloucester County
Homebrewers club -- spread out with beer kegs turned into kettles
and toiled in 80-degree heat over propane cookers to craft a
variety of ales.
</P>
<P>
   At a Princeton homebrew supply shop, about 20 beer enthusiasts
did likewise.
</P>
<P>
   At each location, the beer buffs were celebrating the twelfth
National Homebrew Day, an annual event sponsored by the American
Homebrewers Association based in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Actually an international celebration, the tribute to brewing
and beer styles is in its third year. A recipe for Big Brew 2000's
featured style, American pale ale, was published in the
association's May/June edition of ''Zymurgy,'' a magazine titled
after the process of making fermented beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers expected this year's event to include 3,000 people at
250 registered sites from nine countries -- including the United
States, Poland, Japan, England, Germany, Austria and South Africa.
The target volume for Big Brew 2000: 300 barrels of beer. (A barrel
is 31 gallons.)
</P>
<P>
   Each participating site is asked to notify the AHA of its
attendance and how many gallons of beer brewed.
</P>
<P>
   Big Brew '99 united 2,180 people from 47 states and eight
countries to brew a recipe of a milk stout -- a sweeter tasting,
full-bodied cousin of the classic stout style most commonly
associated with Guinness. The American pale ale recipe for this
year is an imitation of Sierra Nevada Pale Ale, a microbrewery beer
from California.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have the flexibility to do what they want with their
brew kettles, but most will be brewing the pale ale,'' said Paul
Gatza, director of the AHA based in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   In Turnersville, behind Beer Crafters supply shop, Blaise
Fougere of Cinnaminson brewed a Belgian style ale called abbey
double.
</P>
<P>
   Fougere unloaded his brewing gear from the back of his van and
displayed a 1957 black-and-white photo of his father, Simon,
siphoning beer from a wooden barrel into jars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Homebrew and heritage,'' Fougere said, adding that when he
started brewing he didn't know of his father's experience. ''When I
let him know, he told me he had the picture of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the lot, Julian Mason lent an international flavor to the
day. Mason, a native of Worcester, England, who now lives in
Winslow Township, was brewing American ale. A diver who works on
dam projects, Mason has lived in the United Stated for almost 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I first came here, I couldn't stand the beer,'' he said.
''It was refreshing perhaps because it was cold when the weather
was hot. I think now with all the microbreweries, there's a lot of
good really good beer here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Princeton, shop owner Joe Bair hosted about 20 brewers from
the club, Princeton And Local Environs Ale and Lager Enjoyment
Society. ''That's an awfully long thing to say. It sounds like
something the Reagan administration would make up. It's easier to
just say PALE ALES,'' Bair said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're doing about 45 gallons. It's less than last year; we had
about 30 people last year and did 65 gallons.''
</P>
<P>
   From his store's back yard, where he has garden of hop vines
snaking 12 feet up and along a trellis, Bair and his crowd brewed
what he dubbed a ''California red'' beer, using a specially malted
barley from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ''It came out red, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.beertown.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
