<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Delves Into Balkans Problem  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY ULBRICH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FURNAS, Azores Islands (AP) -- European Union foreign ministers
took a critical look Saturday at EU efforts in the Balkans, while
Austria pressed for the lifting of sanctions imposed over the
presence of far-right elements in its government.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Solana, the EU's chief of foreign and security policy,
urged the 15 foreign ministers to help Serbia's independent media
and send aid through local governments held by opponents of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Aid to Serbia is needed because Milosevic is ''clearly moving to
silence independent voices in the run-up to the elections,'' Solana
said, referring to the local voting in Serbia that must be held by
November.
</P>
<P>
   EU finance ministers are expected next week to authorize about
$20 million for programs in support of June 11 municipal elections
in Montenegro, the pro-Western republic that along with Serbia
makes up the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers are gathered for two days in an informal session
in this town on Portugal's mid-Atlantic Azores islands.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, they are expected to decide whether to send a
European mission to the Philippines, where rebels are holding more
than two dozen hostages, including citizens of Germany, France and
Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Austria continued to plead here for a lifting of the bilateral
sanctions imposed by the other 14 EU member countries after
Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel formed a government with the far
right Freedom Party in February.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian government said Friday it might hold a nonbinding
referendum giving Austrians a chance to express their views on the
sanctions, which have affected diplomatic, sporting and cultural
ties. The symbolic vote would be aimed at embarrassing Austria's EU
partners.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Party has drawn criticism over its perceived
anti-immigrant stance and comments by its former leader, Joerg
Haider, in praise of some aspects of the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope it will not come to a referendum,'' Austrian Foreign
Minister Benita Ferrero-Waldner said. Such a vote would show ''that
the majority of the Austrian people stands behind the government
and wants the lifting of the sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   They EU ministers also discussed how to breathe new life into
talks on overhauling the European Union's convoluted
decision-making rules.
</P>
<P>
   EU governments are deadlocked in reform talks that began in
February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
