<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grave Robberies Baffle Madagascar  </HEADLINE>
By KATYA ROBINSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) -- A spate of grave robberies in
eastern Madagascar has baffled officials and sparked an uproar over
the theft of bones in a culture where people worship their
ancestors and revere tombs.
</P>
<P>
   Police have arrested about 50 people in recent weeks for
breaking into tombs and stealing and selling bones.
</P>
<P>
   Local media have speculated the robberies are linked to
international trafficking in human bones for unknown medical
applications, while others wonder if unknown cults or tribal
rivalries are involved.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who was caught allegedly buying bones from the grave
robbers for up to $40 a pound was arrested in March, but officials
said they do not yet know her motive.
</P>
<P>
   Grave robbing has been a chronic problem in eastern Madagascar
since 1996, with 1,000 tombs desecrated, investigators say. Police
have seized two tons of human bones, mostly in routine traffic
stops, since they began investigating the crimes three years ago.
In the past several weeks, the number of crimes has escalated
though authorities are at a loss to explain the increase.
</P>
<P>
   Grave robbers who broke into five tombs last week took the
skeletons but not the skulls of female corpses, which usually are
separated from men in collective family tombs. As in other cases,
they left the male corpses undisturbed, though they threw the
bodies of the recently buried outside the tombs.
</P>
<P>
   In Madagascar, the dead are traditionally buried in communal
family tombs that are often far more elaborate structures than the
homes of the living. Families spend years of savings on the stone
or cement tombs the size of small houses.
</P>
<P>
   Every few years, families exhume the bodies in elaborate
ceremonies, rewrap the bones and dance with the shrouded remains
lifted shoulder-high before replacing them on shelves in the tombs.
Malagasy people believe their dead relatives have a godlike status
and have the power to bring fortune or tragedy to the living.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's simply shocking to do this here. It exhibits the most
profound disrespect for families,'' said Mamy Rakotobe, national
director of cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The dead are key to the Malagasy's sense of self, and the loss
of their remains is akin to wiping out the identities of the
living, he said. However, money could drive the desperate to
desecrate a tomb in the world's 13th poorest nation, says Rakotobe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
