<HEADLINE> S.C. Governor Seeks Flag Resolution  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- South Carolina Gov. Jim Hodges on Saturday
urged state lawmakers not to adjourn until the Confederate flag
dispute is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to solve that problem, my friends, and we will not
leave Columbia until we do,'' Hodges said at the Democratic Party's
state convention.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative session ends June 1, but Hodges has the
authority to call a special session.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP has been urging people and companies to boycott South
Carolina until the Confederate flag comes down from the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday will start debating a Senate-passed bill to
remove the flag from the Statehouse dome and fly a similar banner
at a monument in front of the Capitol honoring Confederate
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic state Rep. John Scott said he will not support the
Senate bill because the NAACP opposes the flag's visibility in the
plan. NAACP officials say they will continue the boycott if the
Legislature approves the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
