<HEADLINE> Colombian Soccer Referee Shot Dead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Gunmen shot and killed a
semiprofessional soccer referee after forcing his car off a road in
western Colombia, authorities said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Fajardo was shot five times in the Friday night attack on
a highway outside Cali, the capital of Valle State, police said.
The motive was not immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''They ended the life of an extraordinary person who cared a lot
for his fellow referees,'' Edgar Velez, a member of the state
referees association where Fajardo was president, said on local
radio.
</P>
<P>
   The killing was only the latest in a rash of violent incidents
this year involving Colombian sports figures.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, a national sharpshooting champion used his target
rifle to kill two assailants in an attempted kidnapping or robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Days earlier, rebels had kidnapped a former national soccer team
member, releasing him 48 hours later after a national cry of
outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Two world-class Colombian cyclists have also been kidnapped and
released this year.
</P>
<P>
   The spate of incidents against sports figures has not been seen
as a campaign against athletes. Violent crime is out of control in
this South American country, which has the world's highest
kidnapping rate and a decades-old civil conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
