<HEADLINE> Romanian Couple Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- A Romanian couple who fled Romania's
communist regime by stealing a light aircraft were arrested when
they applied for new Romanian passports, police said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking a communist-era prison sentence passed in 1986, police
arrested the couple Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Agneta and Iosif Hasz, aged 39 and 44 respectively, fled Romania
in August 1983 after stealing a crop-duster plane, according to a
statement issued by police in Satu Mare, northern Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Hasz and the plane's pilot, Dumitru Morar, were working at Satu
Mare airport, 280 miles northwest of Bucharest. They said at the
time they intended to use the plane for a recreation flight.
</P>
<P>
   The three fled to Austria, where they requested political
asylum, and then left for Germany, where they obtained German in
addition to their Romanian citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Romanian authorities convicted the three in absentia in 1986 of
''stealing and embezzlement,'' and sentenced them to between 15 and
20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, the couple returned to Romania twice to renew their
passport without any problem. But this time the Satu Mare police
arrested them on the basis of the communist-era prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Agneta Hasz was immediately released under the statute of
limitation. Her husband is to stay in jail until July, but the
couple planned to hire a lawyer to have the sentence annulled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
