<HEADLINE> Arab League Wants Israelis Tried  </HEADLINE>
By TAREK EL-TABLAWY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- The Arab League on Saturday called for
convening an international criminal court to try Israelis
responsible for a massacre of Lebanese civilians in 1996, equating
it with Israeli demands for justice for Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time that the League has formally made such a
demand on the Qana bombing. Resurrecting past grudges echoes the
frustration and outrage among Arabs over Israel's two-day
bombardment this week against Lebanon -- despite its plans to pull
out of the country within the next two months after years of
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-member body demanded in a resolution that Israel be held
accountable and forced to pay compensation for the ''human losses
and financial and economic harm resulting from its attacks on
Lebanese lands.''
</P>
<P>
   It said the Arab League expresses ''support for Lebanon's call
to form an ... international criminal court to try Israeli war
criminals who carried out the 1996 Qana massacre ... and other
Israeli massacres for which Lebanon served as a stage.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 18, 1996, at the height of an Israeli bombing campaign
against Hezbollah, about 800 villagers took refuge at the base of
the Fijian contingent of the U.N. peacekeeping force, believing
they would be safe there. Instead, the flimsy huts in which they
were sheltering came under fire, and about 100 civilians died.
</P>
<P>
   Israel said it hit the U.N. compound by mistake. The attack led
to an agreement between Israel and Hezbollah guerrillas that
neither would use or target civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest attacks are a violation of that agreement, the
Arab League said. This is not the first time Israel has been
accused of breaking that deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every day Arab countries take a step toward peace and Israel
unfortunately moves back from it 1,000 miles,'' Arab League
Secretary-General Esmat Abdel-Meguid told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to justify the League's demand, saying Israel also asks
for compensation for the Jewish victims of Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In two days of attacks and counterattacks, Israel early Friday
knocked out power stations near Beirut and in northern Lebanon. The
strikes were retaliation for a Hezbollah rocket attack on northern
Israel that killed a soldier and injured 26 people. Hezbollah said
its barrage was to avenge two civilian deaths on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
