<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Questions Zimbabwe Leader  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- In a meeting with President Robert
Mugabe Saturday, visiting U.N. Security Council delegates
criticized the Zimbabwe military's alleged involvement in dealing
diamonds and other mineral wealth in central Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Council members did not say how Mugabe responded to the
allegations that his military was dealing in riches in the central
Congolese city of Mbuji Mayi.
</P>
<P>
   ''We said that plundering a country was a bad thing, and that it
had to stop,'' Dutch Ambassador Peter Van Walsum said.
</P>
<P>
   The mission, led by U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke, planned
the meeting to keep Congo's flagging peace process on track. The
war pits Congo's government against numerous rebel and militia
groups in shifting fronts scattered across a vast nation of jungles
and savanna.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe deployed more than 10,000 soldiers to back Congo's
government, while Zimbabwe faces a growing economic and political
crisis at home. Mugabe refused Saturday to speak with journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The council members discussed setting up a panel of experts to
look into foreign forces extracting minerals in Congo, according to
French Ambassador Jean David Levitte. Although Congo is nearly
devoid of economic infrastructure, warring sides in the Central
African country have been attracted by some of the richest natural
resources on the planet, including uranium, gold, diamonds and
other precious minerals.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda, which back rival Congolese rebel factions,
have been accused of profiting from Congo's bountiful natural
resources in the east, including timber and gems.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council delegation was on the third day of its
visit to five African countries somehow involved in the war. The
rebels have allies in Uganda and Rwanda, while Congolese President
Laurent Kabila is backed by Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia. Other
African countries, including South Africa and Zambia, have tried to
help mediate peace.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the council's tour has been to boost Congo's peace
prospects, and to prepare the climate for a 5,500-member U.N.
observer mission. On Thursday, the Congolese government signed an
agreement giving access and safety assurances to U.N. observers
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said Saturday that Friday's fighting between nominal
allies Uganda and Rwanda in eastern Congo had merely been an
''aberration,'' and he insisted that a cease-fire was holding.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in the city of Kisangani ''doesn't surprise us,''
he said, explaining that it was normal for peace initiatives to
face setbacks. ''But it is not acceptable. The fighting must come
to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Kisangani was calm Saturday, following the daylong dual that
left at least 10 civilians dead and another 100 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council delegation is to visit Rwanda and Uganda on
Sunday. It has already traveled to Congo and Zambia
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
