<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prejean Pushes Prisoner Help  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- Death penalty opponent and activist Sister
Helen Prejean says prisoners shouldn't be treated like refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do we have to throw people away?'' asked Prejean, author of
''Dead Man Walking.'' ''If we can recycle soda pop bottles, maybe
we can recycle human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Prejean spoke to more than 85 people at a $100-a-plate luncheon
Friday to raise funds for Dismas House, an Albuquerque-based
nonprofit program helping parolees integrate into society.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana nun said the death penalty serves no purpose other
than to drag society into the same violence of the felons.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is imitating their violence the only way?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Modern societies have other ways to incapacitate people,''
Prejean said. ''That's what incarceration is for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
