<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New prince of the church faces a complex archdiocese  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The new archbishop of New York will walk a
spiritual tightrope, balancing traditional teachings with today's
modern twists as he takes on America's most prominent Roman
Catholic post.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, he'll be Pope John Paul II's point man to the
world's most powerful nation. But his flock -- including those who
question birth control and women seeking a greater role in the
church -- may not follow easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''We, the baptized, are the church. We really don't look to the
hierarchy,'' says Sister Mary Boys, professor of practical theology
at New York's Union Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Some problems of the successor to the late Cardinal John
O'Connor are peculiar to New York, with its spectacular mix of
cultures and languages. But others reflect the challenge of the
Roman Catholic Church across the country in an age when strict
rules are ever more open to question.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,700-square-mile New York archdiocese stretches from
Manhattan to the Bronx, Staten Island and seven counties north of
the city, ministering to 2.4 million faithful. The archdiocese
faces tight finances, a diminishing supply of priests and nuns, and
a radical change in the population to which it ministers.
</P>
<P>
   New York, the nation's third largest Catholic diocese after Los
Angeles and Chicago, has revolved around Irish immigrants since the
19th century, followed by a large influx of Italians in the early
20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the reason why O'Connor -- the latest in a long line of
Irish-American archbishops -- learned Spanish: more than a third of
New York's Catholics are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the possible successors to O'Connor have Irish
names, the new archbishop must serve the Latino parishioners, too,
along with a fast growing population of ethnic Asian Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   About two miles from the bronze portals of St. Patrick's on
Fifth Avenue is St. Elizabeth's Church in the Washington Heights
neighborhood, where working-class Puerto Ricans and Dominicans
struggle to feed their children.
</P>
<P>
   ''The church is under pressure -- financial pressure, the
pressure of the drug scene and the sex scene in the neighborhood,
the pressure of families that aren't able to stay intact,'' says
the Rev. Gerry Walsh, St. Elizabeth's Irish-American pastor.
</P>
<P>
   He says one of the biggest problems faced by the American
Catholic Church is that the number of immigrants is rising while
the number of priests and nuns is dropping -- by about 50 percent in
the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many parishes are now staffed by lay people and
priests from the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to keep the ship afloat. People are hungry for
religious faith,'' says Walsh, 58, who presides over Masses in
Spanish and English to meet the needs of new and longtime
parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   Juliassa Figueroa, who worships at St. Elizabeth's, doesn't mind
that the church's pastor is not Hispanic. Walsh, she says, ''is a
great pastor. I always see him around talking to people on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   But she says she misses the close-knit friendships from her
native Puerto Rico, the sense of community that was carried over in
the church.
</P>
<P>
   ''People over there were more together, we knew each other,''
says Figueroa, 32, who stays home with her baby while her husband
works as a building superintendent. ''Here, you come to church, you
see the people in church, and then you don't see them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The new archbishop will replace a cardinal who was a powerhouse,
both spiritual and temporal. In the world's media capital, he would
appear with politicians and celebrities, and his comments on
explosive social issues in Sunday homilies were news.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor was no beancounter. There are shortfalls in the
archdiocese's $527 million annual budget. The money supports 413
parishes, 17 hospitals, 238 Catholic elementary schools and 55 high
schools, among other church institutions tended by the
archdiocese's almost 900 priests and about 3,700 nuns, as well as
1,000 lay workers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the financial troubles, the new archbishop will encounter
parishioners -- like those across the country -- who are increasingly
setting their own agenda for what Catholicism means. Some attend
Mass while holding opinions on abortion, birth control and openly
gay or lesbian lifestyles that run counter to official Vatican
teachings.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor held to the Vatican line on such social issues, as well
as in failing to encourage the promotion of women, who are taking a
greater role in church affairs, to higher positions of authority.
</P>
<P>
   When death came for the archbishop Wednesday, loud accolades
mixed with whispers of his strained relationship with some women in
the church and female theologians seeking church leadership roles
or even ordination as priests.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many, many women theologically trained and educated
for pastoral positions, but I'm not mindful of anything Cardinal
O'Connor has done to make it possible for such women to preach,''
says Sister Boys, a member of the Sisters of the Holy Names of
Jesus and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   One New York newspaper even suggested that a woman should
replace O'Connor -- technically possible, since a cardinal need not
be a priest.
</P>
<P>
   ''One more nice old guy -- or even a nasty old guy -- is not going
to be able to patch the leaks in the plumbing,'' wrote columnist
Jim Dwyer in the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The comment suggests one paramount quality that the Rev. Thomas
Reese, editor in chief of the Catholic magazine America, says the
archbishop of New York must have: ''He's got to have thick skin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
