<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Commander Defends Troops  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANDA ACEH, Indonesia (AP) -- A local military chief testified
Saturday in a landmark human rights trial that his soldiers were
acting in self-defense when they killed 57 civilians in an
anti-rebel operation last year.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Syafnil Armen, chief of Lilawangsa Military Command, said
the July 23 attack by 300 soldiers on Beutong Ateuh, a remote
village in West Aceh, was aimed at capturing separatist leader
Tengku Bantaqiah.
</P>
<P>
   Bantaqiah, a former political prisoner and preacher at the
hamlet's Islamic boarding school, was killed along with 56 of his
students. He was a prominent supporter of the Free Aceh Movement,
which has been waging a bloody independence struggle since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of 25 soldiers and one civilian for the murders is
regarded as a test of the new government's resolve to rein in the
military, which committed numerous human rights abuses in Aceh
during the dictatorship of ex-president Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, presided over by a panel of military and civilian
judges, opened last month in the provincial capital of Banda Aceh.
It is expected to last several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Armen testified that, on its way to the village, the army unit
was ambushed twice by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the operation, I received reports that 31 people
including Bantaqiah were shot dead,'' Armen said. ''The shootings
... were inevitable because the rebels first attacked the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those charged in the killings were enlisted men, and the
highest ranking officer was a captain. The commander of the
operation, Lt. Col. Sudjono, has been missing since he was named a
suspect in November.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels belonging to the Free Aceh Movement have been fighting to
secede from Indonesia. More than 5,000 people have been killed in
the past decade, including about 300 since the beginning of this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
