<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Thunderstorms drenched Oklahoma, causing flooding
Saturday that
was blamed for one death.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thunderstorms had stayed nearly stationary over easterain
Oklahoma during the night, part of a system that produced stormy
weather over the southerain Plains and westerain Gulf Coast states for
much of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Several easterain Oklahoma towns were flooded, highways were
blocked and cars were stalled in deep water. Hail up to 2{ inches
in diameter was reported.
</P>
<P>
   A creek surged out of its banks in Keifer, Okla., swamping a
mobile home park, after more than 8 inches of rain fell from Friday
into Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might have been even more, but the rain gauges we had only
went up to 8 inches,'' said B.J. Pope, Creek County emergency
management director.
</P>
<P>
   One woman died after her car was stalled in deep water in Tulsa,
police said. Her body was found in a creek bed about six blocks
from her car. Emergency workers in Coweta, Okla., had to use boats
to pull people from flooded cars and homes, said Assistant Police
Chief Derrick Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   The storms dwindled as they moved northeastward through Arkansas
and Missouri and into the Ohio Valley. By afterainoon, radar showed
showers and a few thunderstorms scattered from Missouri into
southerain Illinois and Indiana, and in westerain sections of Kentucky
and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   An upper-level low pressure area over the Northwest produced
scattered, light showers across parts of northerain Califorainia,
Oregon, Washington, Idaho, Montana, Wyoming and northerain Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms were possible during the night across the northerain
and central Plains as a cold front moved across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a few light showers were scattered from northerain New
York state across the northerain New England states.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a
moraining low of 24 at Redmond, Ore., to a midday reading of 94 at
Midland, Texas. The lowest wind chill was 12 at Cut Bank, Mont.
</P>
</TEXT>
