<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel To Help Border Civilians  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The Israeli government has prepared a $450
million plan to help civilians on the Lebanese border cope with
economic and security problems they could face after Israeli forces
withdraw in the next two months, an official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak will submit the proposal to the
cabinet for approval on May 14, his spokesman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 years now the Israeli army has occupied a strip of land
in south Lebanon to protect the border against guerrilla attacks.
But Barak has promised to withdraw the troops by early July, after
which residents fear they will be much more exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the aid package is a $76 million program to build
roads further away from the border than the ones that exist now.
But most of the other items in the plan were aimed at reducing
unemployment and boosting investment in industry, agriculture and
tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors in the border towns have repeatedly complained that,
aside from Lebanese guerrillas launching periodic Katyusha rocket
attacks, the government ignores their economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday and Friday scores of rockets landed in the area,
killing a soldier and injuring a number of civilians. About 200,000
civilians spent more than 24 hours in bomb shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was made in response to the killing of two Lebanese
women by an Israeli-backed Lebanese militia.
</P>
<P>
   Israel reacted to Thursday's attack by bombing two Lebanese
power stations, a guerrilla ammunition dump and the highway
connecting Beirut to Damascus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
