<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Province Under Quarantine  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ULAN BATOR, Mongolia (AP) -- Mongolia's southeastern province of
Dornogobi is under quarantine after an outbreak of foot-and-mouth
disease, a civil defense spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The government posted troops at entry and exit points to seal
off the province after 140 animals were reported dead, said
spokesman Col. Yondoniin Tserendavaa of the Mongolian Civil Defense
Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Quarantine officials were testing another 17,000 animals for the
disease as they awaited a shipment of vaccine from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the situation under control,'' Tserendavaa said.
</P>
<P>
   Outbreaks of the disease -- which is deadly to cloven-hoofed
animals but not people -- have also been reported in Japan and South
Korea, causing neighboring countries including Mongolia to ban
exports of meat and livestock from both countries.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak was a blow to Mongolian herders, who were already
devastated by drought and unusually cold and snowy weather that has
killed more than 2.2 million head of livestock so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The combined disasters have caused meat prices in the capital,
Ulan Bator, to triple since March.
</P>
<P>
   The quarantine in Dornogobi caused local train service to be
suspended, leaving some 500 passengers stranded and complaining of
food shortages, officials said. The international service from
Beijing was also not making stops in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Mongolian experts said they believed the disease originated in
China. Chinese authorities, however, have said their herds are free
of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease reported
in Mongolia since 1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
