<HEADLINE> Rebels Claim Capture in Chad  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN LINNEE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Rebels fighting to oust Chadian President
Idriss Deby said Saturday they had captured an army garrison in the
country's north.
</P>
<P>
   Kailan said the garrison at Zouar, a small town with an airfield
560 miles north of the capital, N'Djamena, fell without a fight on
Friday. The day before, rebels took Zoumri, a smaller army post
east of Bardai, without firing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government troops just fled south when they saw our guys
coming,'' said Kailan Ahmed Touer, Paris-based spokesman for the
Movement for Democracy and Justice in Chad, or MDJT.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't have the will to fight,'' Kailan said of the
government troops.
</P>
<P>
   A rebel statement claimed that government soldiers attacked
civilians as they fled, killing livestock and poisoning wells in
the semi-desert region.
</P>
<P>
   Kailan also said it was ''common knowledge'' that Libya is
ferrying Chadian government troops by air from the military base at
Faya-Largeau to the Libyan air base at Aozou-Tanoua astride the
Chad-Libyan border.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately possible to obtain comment on the rebel
claims from the government in N'Djamena.
</P>
<P>
   Kailan said the rebel's next objective was the oasis of Bardai,
the capital of Chad's mountainous Tebesti region. Zouar is 75 miles
south of Bardai, Zoumri is to the east. A year ago the rebels
claimed to have Bardai surrounded.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners ruled Chad, a landlocked poor country, from
independence from France in 1960 to 1980 and were then succeeded by
a series of rebel leaders from the north.
</P>
<P>
   With the assistance of France, Deby ousted Hissene Habre in
December 1990. Habre, also with French help, ousted his former
comrade-in-arms Goukouni Oueddei, who now lives in exile between
Algeria and Libya, in May 1982. Libya helped put Goukouni in power
in 1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
