<HEADLINE> Sharif Accused of Corruption  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Deposed premier Nawaz Sharif's
government tapped the telephones of judges, journalists, opposition
politicians and leading businessmen and indulged in massive
corruption, the attorney general said, according to Saturday
newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Aziz A. Munshi told Pakistan's Supreme Court
Friday that the Sharif government had bugged scores of telephones,
including those of Chief Justice Irshad Hasan Khan, former Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto and politician Imran Khan, the
English-language daily The News said.
</P>
<P>
   Munshi was appearing before the Supreme Court to defend the Oct.
12 military takeover that ousted Sharif from power. Army Chief Gen.
Pervez Musharraf overthrew the elected government in a bloodless
coup, charging that Sharif's regime was rife with corruption and
economic mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Munshi said the telephones of several newspaper organizations
and international news agencies -- including The Associated Press
and Reuters -- were being tapped by spy agencies on the order of the
deposed government.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear if the bugs had been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's party gave no immediate response after Munshi's
allegations in court.
</P>
<P>
   The military regime found Sharif guilty of hijacking, and
sentenced him to two concurrent life sentences. He is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Munshi also accused Sharif of misusing power to buy state-owned
land at below market value. He said the ex-prime minister was
guilty of tax evasion and of defaulting on his bank loans, the
English-language daily Dawn reported.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif, whose family's industrial empire is valued at $3
billion, paid just $16 in tax in one year, Munshi said.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption is a major issue in Pakistan, where Sharif and Bhutto
were both dismissed from power on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   The military-led government has promised to root out corruption
and collect the stolen wealth. It is pursing several corruption
cases against Sharif, Bhutto and their former aides. Both former
premiers deny the charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
