<HEADLINE> Leader: Ethnic Cleansing in Cyprus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
alleged Saturday that the Turkish community of Cyprus had suffered
''ethnic cleansing'' long before the Balkans did.
</P>
<P>
   In his last official visit to the breakaway Turkish Cypriot
state, Demirel was referring to the strife between Turkish and
Greek Cypriots in the years before Turkey's 1974 invasion, which
left an estimated 2,500 people dead on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ethnic cleansing was tried here first, before
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Kosovo,'' Demirel told a crowd of about one
thousand people.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his long political career, Demirel has taken a close
interest in the Turkish Cypriot community. His term ends on May 16;
his replacement is top judge Ahmet Necdet Sezer.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus has been split since the invasion, which was launched
after a short-lived coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The self-declared Turkish Cypriot state in the north is
recognized only by Turkey, which has some 35,000 troops stationed
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
