<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Connor Successor Faces Challenges  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The new archbishop of New York will have to walk
a spiritual tightrope, balancing traditional teachings with
contemporary challenges as he takes over America's most prominent
Roman Catholic pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   He will be Pope John Paul II's point man in the world's most
powerful nation. But his flock -- including those who support birth
control and women seeking a greater role in the church -- may not
follow easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''We, the baptized, are the church. We really don't look to the
hierarchy,'' said Sister Mary Boys, professor of practical theology
at New York's Union Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Some problems facing the successor to Cardinal John O'Connor,
who died Wednesday at age 80 after 16 years as cardinal, are
peculiar to New York, with its spectacular mix of cultures and
languages. But others reflect the challenge of the Catholic Church
across the country in an age when strict rules are ever more open
to question.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,700-square-mile New York archdiocese, with 2.4 million
faithful, faces tight finances, a diminishing supply of priests and
nuns and a radical change in the population to which it ministers.
</P>
<P>
   It is the nation's third largest Catholic diocese after Los
Angeles and Chicago. In the 19th century, it was populated by Irish
immigrants. In the early 20th century, it was Italians.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the reason why O'Connor -- the latest in a long line of
Irish-American archbishops -- learned Spanish: More than a third of
New York's Catholics are now Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   About two miles from the bronze portals of St. Patrick's
Cathedral on Fifth Avenue is St. Elizabeth's Church in the
Washington Heights neighborhood, where working-class Puerto Ricans
and Dominicans struggle to feed their children.
</P>
<P>
   ''The church is under pressure -- financial pressure, the
pressure of the drug scene and the sex scene in the neighborhood,
the pressure of families that aren't able to stay intact,'' said
the Rev. Gerry Walsh, St. Elizabeth's Irish-American pastor.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of the biggest problems faced by the American
Catholic Church is that the number of immigrants is rising while
the number of priests and nuns is dropping -- by about 50 percent in
the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to keep the ship afloat. People are hungry for
religious faith,'' said Walsh, 58, who presides over Masses in
Spanish and English.
</P>
<P>
   Juliassa Figueroa, who worships at St. Elizabeth's, doesn't mind
that the church's pastor is not Hispanic. But she said she misses
the close-knit friendships from her native Puerto Rico, the sense
of community that carried over in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ''People over there were more together, we knew each other,''
said Figueroa, 32. ''Here, you come to church, you see the people
in church, and then you don't see them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The new archbishop will replace a cardinal who was a powerhouse,
both spiritual and temporal. In the world's media capital, he would
appear with politicians and celebrities, and his comments on social
issues in Sunday homilies made news.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor was no bean counter. There are shortfalls in the
archdiocese's $527 million annual budget. The money supports 413
parishes, 17 hospitals, 238 Catholic elementary schools and 55 high
schools, among other church institutions tended by the
archdiocese's almost 900 priests, 3,700 nuns and 1,000 lay workers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the financial troubles, the new archbishop will encounter
parishioners who are increasingly setting their own agenda for what
Catholicism means. Some attend Mass while holding opinions on
abortion, birth control and homosexuality that run counter to
official Vatican teachings.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor held to the Vatican line on such social issues, as well
as in failing to encourage the promotion of women to higher
positions of authority.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many, many women theologically trained and educated
for pastoral positions, but I'm not mindful of anything Cardinal
O'Connor has done to make it possible for such women to preach,''
said Sister Boys, a member of the Sisters of the Holy Names of
Jesus and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   One New York columnist even suggested that a woman should
replace O'Connor -- technically possible, since a cardinal need not
be a priest.
</P>
<P>
   ''One more nice old guy -- or even a nasty old guy -- is not going
to be able to patch the leaks in the plumbing,'' wrote Jim Dwyer in
the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The comment suggests a trait that the Rev. Thomas Reese, editor
in chief of the Catholic magazine America, said the archbishop of
New York must have: ''He's got to have thick skin.''
</P>
<P>
   A top U.S. bishop, Joseph A. Fiorenza of Houston, said in Rome
on Saturday that he expected the Vatican to announce O'Connor's
successor soon. In New York, thousands of people passed through St.
Patrick's Cathedral, where the cardinal's body was to lie until
Monday's funeral Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorenza, who had lunch with the pope at the Vatican on Friday,
said O'Connor's death dominated their conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a big personal loss for the holy father,'' Fiorenza
said. ''The pope relied on him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1751 </TRAILER>
