<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Socialists Shift on NATO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) -- In an effort by the opposition Socialist
Party to boost its image at home and abroad, the party's leader on
Saturday proposed a radical shift in policy toward seeking NATO
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the mass riots that ultimately knocked the
ex-communist Socialist Party from power, Georgi Parvanov said the
party should support Bulgaria's future integration into NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bulgaria will defend better its national interests while being
in NATO rather than staying away from it,'' Parvanov told delegates
of his party's regular congress.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the new position on NATO was ''a natural step
in the party's evolution on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in an attempt to appease hard-liners intent against
Bulgaria's opening up to the West, the moderate party leader said
the issue should be decided in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria hopes to join NATO in its next round of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   Once the most staunch of Soviet allies, the Balkan country won
respect from Western countries during the Kosovo crisis when it
allowed NATO to use the country's airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Parvanov, 43, also called for a new model of government based on
a broad social-liberal coalition, adding the Socialists should
adopt a transparent, non-ideological and pragmatic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Parvanov said that his party would want to participate in a
future Bulgarian government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
