<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Educators Discuss Evolution  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE GOODMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Stephen Jay Gould, a Harvard University
evolution proponent, told a gathering of New England educators
Saturday that the creationism debate is an American ''bizarrity,''
and urged them not to fear its spread.
</P>
<P>
   Gould, who teaches zoology and geology, spoke at a day-long
Brown University symposium on teaching evolution. He encouraged his
audience of teachers, principals and college professors not to fret
over creationist challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ''As insidious as it may seem, at least it's not a worldwide
movement,'' he said. ''I hope everyone realizes the extent to which
this is a local, indigenous, American bizarrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould also urged the audience to keep in perspective the
decision last year by the Kansas Board of Education to approve
science standards that de-emphasize evolution in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''Isn't it absurd though, if what you really want is to get rid
of evolution ... that instead you pass an absurd law -- which the
country's going to laugh at -- making evolution optional,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is ''literally like saying we're going to continue to teach
English, but grammar's optional,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Creationism is the belief that a divine power created the
universe in six days. The theory of evolution holds that humans
evolved from more primitive species.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Fogarty, chairman of the science department at
Providence's Lincoln School, said what happened in Kansas could
happen elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to be ready for it, ready in the sense of being
educated on both sides,'' she said. ''We can't dismiss
(creationism) as being fanaticism, because it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Arnold, a life sciences teacher in Connecticut, said he
excludes discussion of religion from his evolution lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Before he teaches the subject to his students, he tells them:
''I'm going to teach you what is known to be true from a scientific
point of view. You can apply your religion to that.''
</P>
<P>
   If they have questions about how their religion fits in, he says
he isn't afraid to say he doesn't know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not a theologian, I'm a scientist,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
