<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Airbus in Race for Orders  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Forget the gold ring. When it comes to Boeing and
rival Airbus Industrie, the company with the most entries in the
airliner order book is the winner.
</P>
<P>
   And right now they are virtually neck-and-neck for the year.
</P>
<P>
   After lagging behind Boeing for much of the year, Airbus pulled
into a near dead heat Friday with what is said to be a 50-plane
order from the industry's biggest aircraft leasing company.
</P>
<P>
   The order from International Lease Finance Corp. in Los Angeles
is worth more than $3 billion at list prices, the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer reported Saturday. An announcement that a firm
deal has been struck could come next week, the newspaper quoted an
unidentified source as saying.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of April, Airbus had won 120 new orders this year,
according to the company's Web site. The addition of 50 planes for
International Lease would bring the European consortium's total to
170.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has 150 new orders, according to its Web site. But that
does not include a 30-plane order announced Thursday by American
Trans Air. The ATA order will not be added to Boeing's total until
a final purchase agreement is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus edged Boeing for the first time ever last year, when it
landed about 60 percent of all new orders for planes with more than
100 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Top Boeing executives say the Seattle company is well positioned
to win the majority of new airplane orders in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ''As clearly as I can say this, I think we are in a great
position vis a vis Airbus,'' Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said at
the company's annual meeting Monday in Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.airbus.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.boeing.com
</P>
</TEXT>
