<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finger Sidelines Brewers' Jenkins  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- In a season full of bad breaks for the
Milwaukee Brewers, this one was the worst yet.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Jenkins, the Brewers' leader in nearly every hitting
category, will be out for one month after breaking a bone in the
middle finger of his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee put Jenkins on the 15-day disabled list Saturday after
a 3-2 loss to Montreal. He was held out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins hurt the finger on Friday night while swinging at a
pitch in the second inning of Milwaukee's 10-2 loss to Montreal. He
lost control of his bat on the swing, and it flew into the crowd
and hit the arm of a female spectator who left the game wearing a
soft cast.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins came out in the fifth inning and said he thought he had
merely sprained the finger, which didn't appear swollen or crooked.
But X-rays of the injury taken Saturday morning revealed the break.
A team spokesman said he's expected to miss a month.
</P>
<P>
   His loss is a blow for the Brewers, whose team batting average
is already a majors-worst .227. Jenkins, the team's cleanup hitter
and everyday left fielder, has been the only reliable offensive
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee (10-20) has lost 15 of its last 19 games and is 2-7 on
its current homestand, which ends Sunday. The Brewers, already nine
games behind NL Central-leading St. Louis, have lost seven straight
series and will start a seven-game road trip Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins has hit 11 homers, tying him with four players for the
NL lead entering Saturday. He leads Milwaukee's regular players in
batting average (.298), RBIs (23), runs (19), hits (31), total
bases (69) and slugging percentage (.663).
</P>
<P>
   He had homered in three of the previous six games before his
injury, and he had hit a homer in each of the Brewers' last seven
series. He is also tied with Arizona's Steve Finley for the NL lead
in outfield assists (four).
</P>
<P>
   The team said the injury was a fracture to the middle joint of
the finger. Jenkins dressed for the game against Montreal and
caught the game's ceremonial first pitch, but was held out of the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Once a deep offensive team that played high-scoring games, the
Brewers have very little hitting depth this season. In an attempt
to improve Milwaukee's woeful pitching, first-year GM Dean Taylor
traded several vital components of the Brewers' fairly potent 1999
lineup during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Former Brewers infield starters Jeff Cirillo, Fernando Vina and
Jose Valentin are all thriving in their new homes, but except for
3-2 starter Jimmy Haynes, Taylor's pitching acquisitions haven't
made a dent in Milwaukee's losing ways.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' break is the second major hand injury suffered by a
critical member of the Brewers' lineup in two seasons. All-Star
outfielder Jeromy Burnitz, who is currently mired in a 3-for-34
slump, missed a month of last season after breaking a bone in his
hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1904 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giants 6, Rockies 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Shawn Estes scattered nine hits and Jeff
Kent went 3-for-3 with a triple and two runs scored Saturday as the
San Francisco Giants shut out the Colorado Rockies for the second
straight day, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have won six straight and are 12-2 following a 4-11
start.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, which led the majors with a .300 batting average
coming in, has been blanked in consecutive games for the first time
since starting play in 1993. The Rockies had scored 72 runs in
their previous six games before the series.
</P>
<P>
   Estes (2-1) retired the side in order just twice, but worked out
of jams to win his second straight start. He struck out five and
walked three in his fifth career shutout and sixth complete game.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco went ahead with an unearned run in the fourth
against Rolando Arrojo (1-3). Kent scored from second with two outs
when second baseman Mike Lansing overthrew first base on Armando
Rios' slow infield chopper up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mueller's sacrifice fly made it 2-0 in the fifth, and San
Francisco added three runs in the sixth. Kent tripled and scored on
an RBI double by Rios. Doug Mirabelli added a two-run single for a
5-0 lead, and Mueller doubled a run in the eighth off Mike DeJean.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, pitching for the first time since April 20 following a
stint on the disabled list caused by a strained left hamstring,
allowed all five runs -- four earned -- seven hits and four walks in
five-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado advanced runners to scoring position four times against
Estes. The Rockies loaded the bases with one out in the third, but
Todd Helton grounded into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Rockies are 0-for-12 with runners in scoring position
in the series. ... To make room for Arrojo on the roster, the
Rockies optioned RHP Giovanni Carrara to Colorado Springs. ...
Giants OF Barry Bonds was given the day off. ... Kent is 13-for-32
on the homestand with three home runs and eight RBIs. ... Estes is
3-0 in four starts against the Rockies since 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
