<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patient Drysdale Wins The Derby  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- The waiting game is over for Neil
Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale won the Kentucky Derby on Saturday with Fusaichi
Pegasus, eight years after enduring the frustration of scratching
A.P. Indy on race morning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, A.P. Indy turned up with a bruised foot on Derby Day
and never left the barn. The injury also kept him out of the
Preakness. But the colt came back to win the Belmont and was voted
horse of the year, giving Drysdale some consolation.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly didn't need any this week.
</P>
<P>
   The 1{-length victory Saturday by the Japanese-owned horse,
whose tongue-twister of a name often leads Drysdale to call him
''the colt,'' completed a dream week for the trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, 52, was elected to racing's Hall of Fame on Tuesday.
D. Wayne Lukas followed the same path last year, getting into the
hall days before Charismatic won the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very humbling week and very rewarding,'' Drysdale said.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale is as cool as Fusaichi Pegasus can be contentious. He's
unfailingly polite, but it's obvious Drysdale doesn't thrive on the
spotlight like some of his fellow trainers.
</P>
<P>
   He's loathe to reveal much, if any, emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know I don't answer touchy-feely questions,'' he told
reporters asking what it meant to win the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale learned the two P's -- patience and planning -- during
four years as an assistant to the late Hall of Fame trainer Charlie
Whittingham in the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, a former English teacher, opened his own stable in
1983. He trains on the same Southern California circuit as Lukas
and Bob Baffert, and is successful in a low-profile kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   His horses earned more than $4 million last year, and 124 of his
266 starters finished in the money. Drysdale was even better in
1998. He won a career-high 73 races and finished fourth among the
nation's trainers with earnings of $6.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1905 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ky. Derby Trainers Examine Race  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE BAILEY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Jenine Sahadi is ready for life to return
to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks of lofty expectations quickly evaporated as Sahadi,
trainer of Santa Anita Derby winner The Deputy, watched in
frustration Saturday as her prize colt finished 14th in the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Had The Deputy crossed the line first, Sahadi would have been
the first female trainer ever to claim the first jewel in horse
racing's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   As tired as she got of answering the endless questions about
female trainers and their quest to win the Derby, she never turned
down an interview. Now, the fuss can die down and she can go back
to being just another trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very disappointed, but not so much for myself,'' a forlorn
Sahadi said. ''I feel bad for the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy, who went off as the second betting choice at 9-2,
trained well after arriving at Churchill Downs and seemed to become
comfortable with the track during workouts. He broke from the gate
strong, running with the leaders early, but tired and fell out of
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was exhausted and just couldn't run,'' she said. ''I guess
you'd call that the beauty of the Kentucky Derby. We'll just pick
up, go home and regroup again.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan favorite Harold Rose, the 88-year-old trainer of Hal's Hope,
spent much of the last two weeks mugging for photos and telling
anyone within earshot of his love for the horse, which he credits
with helping him recover from major heart surgery last August.
</P>
<P>
   The colt led the race entering the final turn, but Rose could
only watch in disappointment as the Florida Derby winner faded and
struggled home to a 16th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, he was in much the same situation as trainer D.
Wayne Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas is no stranger to the Derby winner's circle. He's been
there four times, including last year as trainer of 31-1 shot
Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   He saddled three in Saturday's race, but none would crack the
top half of the 19-horse field. Exchange Rate finished 12th, High
Yield finished 15th and Commendable wound up 17th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000506.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UCLA Wins Men's Volleyball Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) -- UCLA took early leads in the first two
games, then battled back from a 13-8 deficit in the third Saturday
to sweep Ohio State and win the NCAA men's volleyball title for the
18th time.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State built a 5-point lead before UCLA had 5-0 run and
eventually forced overtime in the final match. The Bruins won it
17-15 after taking the first two games 15-8 and 15-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins never trailed in any of the matches and were led by
Evan Thatcher with 15 kills. Chris Fash paced the Buckeyes with 15
kills.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who have won the title more than any team in NCAA
history, gave coach Al Scates his 20th overall win.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA finished the season 29-5. Ohio State went 25-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
