<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secession on Quebec's Agenda, Again  </HEADLINE>
By Jack Branswell, 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Quebec's secessionists were hoping Saturday to
relaunch their bid to split from Canada and become an independent
country.
</P>
<P>
   The Parti Quebecois, the governing party in the province of
Quebec, was holding a weekend policy convention in an effort to
jump start the secessionist movement, which lost two sovereignty
referendum in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   After several years of unpopular budget cuts to eliminate
Quebec's deficit, the party said it is ready once again to address
its ultimate goal -- secession.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard, who also leads the PQ, set the
tone for renewing the debate in his opening speech at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''From this moment on we are going to put the political future
of Quebec front and center in public debate,'' he said. ''We are
going to dare to tell our fellow citizens that the Quebec people
have a job to finish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard's speech was well received by party members, but some
rank-and-file members remained skeptical about when a third
secession referendum would be held. The PQ lost votes in 1980 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we are going to have one in the near future,''
said Claude Lafreniere, a convention delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard says the PQ will hold a referendum as soon as possible,
but has refused to be pinned down on a timetable.
</P>
<P>
   With support for secession hovering around 40 percent, opinion
polls show the majority of Quebecers are fed up with talk of
splitting with Canada and want the provincial government to focus
on bread-and-butter issues like health care and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard's government is also embarking on a controversial plan
to drastically reduce the number of cities and towns in Quebec
through municipal mergers. Many PQ backers oppose the plan and most
analysts think it unlikely that a referendum would be called until
that controversy settles down.
</P>
<P>
   If Bouchard decides to delay a referendum until after the next
election in 2003, the weight of history will be against him: no
Quebec government has won three consecutive mandates since the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard did get over one hurdle on Saturday when PQ delegates,
voting in a leadership review, handed the premier a 91 percent
approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Bouchard still faces a giant task in rekindling the
debate on secession.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec's Intergovernmental Affairs Minister Joseph Facal said
the government is now well-poised to reintroduce the separation
debate because the province has balanced its books and is beginning
to cut taxes. He is unfazed by the stagnant support for secession.
</P>
<P>
   ''In 1995 when we launched the (secession) referendum, support
was at 43 percent and people said 'You guys are nuts.''' ''We ended
at 49.4 percent, whiskers from winning it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 1932 </TRAILER>
