<BODY>
<HEADLINE> George W. Bush Attends Derby  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush says he's not a
betting man -- not even at Saturday's Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't like to lose money,'' Bush explained.
</P>
<P>
   But even politicians aren't allowed to waffle on Derby Day,
where everybody has a favorite even if they don't put down any
money.
</P>
<P>
   So Bush -- the presumptive Republican presidential nominee -- said
he was pulling for The Deputy, a horse trying to become the first
Derby winner trained by a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the story that came true was that the favorite actually
won the race for the first time since 1979. Fusaichi Pegasus took
the lead in mid-stretch and raced home ahead of Aptitude and
Impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had put $2 on the winner, it would have brought him all
of $6.60.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush might want to check with his father if he does
decide to take up wagering. The former president made his first bet
Friday on Secret Status, who won the Kentucky Oaks and paid $295
for the $50 ticket purchased by the elder Bush.
</P>
<P>
   However, the governor disclosed that the tip to his father came
from William S. Farish, a family friend who owns Secret Status and
also happens to be chairman of the board of Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   One of Vice President Al Gore's daughters, Karenna Gore Schiff,
also attended Saturday's Derby -- and also liked The Deputy.
</P>
<P>
   She said that was a tip from her mother, Tipper, who she said
goes by the name in picking her favorite horses. It was not clear
whether Schiff placed a bet -- either for herself or for her mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
