<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 10, Padres 5  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Erubiel Durazo extended his hitting streak to
nine games Saturday with a home run and a double as the Arizona
Diamondbacks beat the San Diego Padres 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell had two hits, including a two-run single as the
Diamondbacks scored six runs off Rodrigo Lopez (0-1) in the second
inning. Pinch-hitter Greg Colbrunn had a two-run double in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sprague was 4-for-4, including two home runs for the Padres.
Sprague has three home runs in two days, raising his season total
to six. Bret Boone hit a three-run homer off Brian Anderson in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson (2-0) allowed four runs and seven hits in seven
innings, and was helped by some strong defense, including three
line-drive catches at shortstop by Tony Womack, one at his shoe
tops, one diving to his left and one soaring high in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Byung-Hyun Kim struck out the side for Arizona in the eighth,
extending his streak of consecutive strikeouts to seven.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, in his second outing since being called up from Triple-A
Las Vegas, allowed six runs and six hits in 1 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo, hitting .433 with four homers and 12 RBIs during his
streak, led off the second with his sixth home run. Steve Finley
doubled and Travis Lee walked, then Kelly Stinnett singled to drive
in Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Fox singled when left fielder Al Martin lost the ball in
the lights, loading the bases for Anderson, who hit a sacrifice
fly.
</P>
<P>
   Womack grounded to second and Boone's throw to the second-base
bag was not in time and off the mark. Bell's single up the middle
drove in two runs, and Arizona made it 6-1 when Luis Gonzalez hit
into a run-scoring fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Boone's three-run homer cut the lead to 6-4 in the fourth.
Arizona added two more in the fourth when reliever Kevin Walker
walked Durazo with the bases loaded and Womack scored on Finley's
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
Notes: San Diego's Eric Owens was 0-for-4 and failed to reach base
for the first time in the 28 games he's played this season. ... In
his first outing, against Atlanta, Lopez allowed one run and five
hits in seven innings. ... Arizona closer Matt Mantei is
rehabilitating his weak shoulder with the same exercise regimen
that Todd Stottlemyre used to come back without surgery from a
partially torn rotator cuff. ... Gonzalez was 0-for-3 and has two
hits in his last 24 at-bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
