<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quotes From Saturday's Ky. Derby  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Quotes from owners, trainers and jockeys
of the 19 3-year-olds who ran in Saturday's 126th Kentucky Derby
(in order of finish):
</P>
<P>
   Fusaishi Pegasus: ''The racing gods smiled on us, the rail
opened and he moved up. He is talented and I'm very proud of him.''
-- trainer Neil Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude: ''I had a great trip, just a perfect trip. I couldn't
have asked for any more that way.'' -- jockey Alex Solis.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment: ''This horse has no speed, so I knew we'd be last
early, going to the first turn, so I just sat there and waited. I'm
proud of him and the way he closed because not too many horses
closed ground today.'' -- jockey Craig Perret.
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready: ''I had a good trip, and right near the eighth
pole I made the lead. I thought I was going to win it. Then the
winner went by me and I knew I couldn't catch him.'' -- jockey John
Velasquez.
</P>
<P>
   Wheelaway: ''I thought we could win it at the eighth pole. The
winner was just so good today.'' -- trainer John Kimmel.
</P>
<P>
   China Visit: ''At the three-eighths pole, I thought we were
going to win. He was really in the bridle, but ran out of steam at
the three-sixteenths pole.'' -- jockey Frankie Dettori.
</P>
<P>
   Curule: ''He ran better than expected, and the Godolphin people
seemed pleased. That makes me happy.'' -- jockey Marlon St. Julien.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve: ''Turning for home, I thought I was home free. I
thought I had him in a good spot, right where I wanted to be.'' --
jockey Robbie Albarado.
</P>
<P>
   War Chant: ''We don't have any excuses. Down the backside, he
came out of the bridle and I couldn't get him to pick it up again
until the eighth pole.'' -- jockey Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Warlock: ''He got hung extremely wide on the second turn.
He wouldn't have won it anyway, but we'll just regroup and find
another spot.'' -- trainer Ken McPeek.
</P>
<P>
   Trippi: ''No excuses. He just got tired.'' -- jockey Jorge
Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange Rate: ''He ran well for a ways.'' -- trainer D. Wayne
Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   Anees: ''I was behind the winner the whole way. But when it came
time to go, it wasn't there. I just ran out of juice.'' -- jockey
Corey Nakatani.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy: ''I could see him clearly and I didn't see anything.
He just didn't fire.'' -- trainer Jenine Sahadi.
</P>
<P>
   High Yield: ''I had a good trip. I just didn't have any horse.''
-- jockey Pat Day.
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope: ''When I saw the fractions, I got nervous. You just
can't go that fast. I did think he would run a little better, but
he went too fast too early.'' -- trainer Harold Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Commendable: ''My jockey said he was strong to the three-eighths
pole, and then he flattened out.'' -- trainer D. Wayne Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   Ronton: ''He never took hold of the track. He just never grabbed
the bridle or seemed comfortable in his stride.'' -- jockey Brice
Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Hall: ''We were eased. He was not hurt, just fatigued.''
-- jockey Shane Sellers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
