<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal attracts few bids for online auction items  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Items related to Cardinal John O'Connor that
went up for sale hours before his death so far have generated
little enthusiasm among customers of the online auction site eBay,
attracting only a few bids.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, auctions still number in the hundreds for items
related to the late John F. Kennedy Jr. And there is a lively
auction board as well for Larry Linville, who recently died after
gaining fame as the character Maj. Frank Burns on the television
classic, MASH. Nearly 400 auctions were listed for Kennedy, who
died in a plane crash last July. Almost 30 items were listed for
Linville.
</P>
<P>
   William Donohue, president of the Catholic League for Religious
and Civil Rights, said he thinks it's just fine that O'Connor items
aren't hot right now.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't surprise me a whole lot,'' he said. ''This is
neither the time nor the place. At least wait until he's in the
grave to start your bids.''
</P>
<P>
   The web domain name of ''Cardinaloconnor.com,'' offered at a
starting price of $500, had attracted no bids as of Saturday. It
was posted shortly before the death of the cardinal was announced
Wednesday. Its anonymous seller said it would be ''perfect for a
Web site dedicated to Cardinal John O'Connor.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other items listed for less than $10 each had received no
bids, including a photograph of O'Connor with former first lady
Rosalynn Carter and another of O'Connor with Mother Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   Three bids had been placed for a book written by O'Connor and
former Mayor Edward Koch.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pursglove, an eBay spokesman, said the scarcity of items
for sale and of bids may stem from a tendency by people not to want
to appear to be trying to capitalize on someone's death.
</P>
<P>
   But he said it was natural for items to be offered for sale
after a death because some people find participating in auctions is
''a way of paying tribute or sharing a memory with their fellow
eBay users.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, he said, might be ''trying to get a little piece of
history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
