<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilot Suspended Over Vieques Claim  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- A pilot for a Puerto Rican commuter
airline has been temporarily suspended for allegedly flying over a
restricted U.S. Navy area on the island of Vieques during
operations to arrest protesters, the airline said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Osvaldo Gonzalez, owner of Vieques Air Link, said that Capt. Jim
Stark, commander of the Roosevelt Roads Naval Station, called him
Friday to complain that one of the airline's planes had flown over
Camp Garcia about an hour after U.S. marshals and FBI agents had
begun clearing protesters from the bombing range on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said that pilot Rolando de Jesus was flying to St.
Croix in the U.S. Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy official complained that De Jesus flew about 100 feet
above the area despite a temporary order to fly no lower than
26,000 feet during the operation, Gonzalez said. The pilot claimed
he was not in the restricted area and flew no lower than 500 feet,
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Navy spokesman Robert Nelson said that someone in the Navy did
contact the Federal Aviation Administration to report ''a possible
violation of airspace,'' but he did not know if it was Stark. He
said he did not have more specific information about the incident
or the airspace restriction.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy would follow up with a written report to the FAA,
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In addition to this, Captain Stark ... did personally contact
the owner of Vieques Air Link to express his concern about these
unsafe acts,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez complained that his small twin-engine planes cannot fly
high enough to avoid the altitude restriction set by the Navy,
which remained in place Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to go 10 miles out of our way and that makes it more
expensive, it's more gasoline and more time,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said the FAA ordered him to suspend De Jesus while it
investigates. FAA officials could not immediately be reached for
comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Stark said he would recommend that the pilot lose his license,
Gonzalez said. Nelson said he was not aware of any statement and
said that Stark could only ''recommend what he believes is the
infraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters camped on Vieques for a little over a year to urge
the Navy to end its training there. Resentments over the six
decades of war games turned to outrage when a civilian guard was
killed by errant bombs on the range in April 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
