<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
The Associated Press
Rex L. Campbell
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Rex L. Campbell, a former radio
broadcaster and longtime University of Utah philosophy professor,
died Wednesday from complications of Parkinson's disease. He was
79.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell worked at KSL radio for 50 years as a news broadcaster
and was famous for his work on the ''Sunday Sound of Music''
program. In 1957, he helped start public television station KUED
and was its manager for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was in the Army during World War II, with his last year
spent in intelligence. After returning home, he earned a doctorate
in philosophy and began teaching at the university.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 years in education, Campbell retired as professor
emeritus in June 1988. He received many awards during his tenure,
including the first distinguished teaching award in the school's
honors program.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, several children, grandchildren and
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
Joe Mansfield
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Joe Mansfield, a former detective
who helped the New York Giants with field security, died Friday
after a long illness. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield joined the Giants in 1976. In addition to his field
security duties, Mansfield helped with locker room operations
during the regular season and at the team's training camp site.
</P>
<P>
Thomas C. ''Chip'' Woods III
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Thomas C. ''Chip'' Woods III, a longtime
telephone company executive and great-grandson of the founder of
Lincoln Telephone Co., died Friday after a five-month battle with
cancer. He was 54.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had been chairman of the telephone company's board since
1993, including when it became Aliant Communications. He retired in
July, when Alltel bought the company.
</P>
<P>
   He was also was president of the Woods Charitable Foundation,
which was begun by his great-grandfather, Frank Woods. The
foundation gave $28 million to Lincoln charities over the past five
decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
