<HEADLINE> Chiapas Bishop To Help Zapatistas  </HEADLINE>
By ALEJANDRO RUIZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLHO, Mexico (AP) -- The new Catholic bishop for the troubled
state of Chiapas promised Zapatista rebels Saturday that he would
intercede on their behalf to resolve a 6-year-old conflict with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to pray and fast in order to rid the demons that exist
here,'' Felipe Arizmendi Esquivel told members of the insurgent
Zapatista National Liberation Army in Polho, one of the main
Zapatista strongholds in this poor southern state.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting marked Arizmendi's first interaction with members of
the diocese of San Cristobal de las Casas, coming just five days
after he officially began in the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas waged a brief armed uprising in January 1994
seeking greater rights for Indians. Sporadic peace talks are at a
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why the bishop put the Zapatistas first on his
agenda, or if the decision in any way indicated that Arizmendi
would become as deeply involved in the conflict as his predecessor,
Bishop Samuel Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi refused to speak with reporters after the meeting. But
he promised the Zapatistas that he would intercede on their behalf
with the government to seek a peaceful end to the conflict and an
end to the persecution of the rebels by paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will offer to speak with the authorities in your name in
order that there is a solution to your just demands,'' he said.
''My obligation is to bring your suffering to the authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   In a previous meeting with another group of Zapatista rebels in
the indigenous village of Chenalho, Arizmendi asked the rebels to
live as God wants them to, without resorting to weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi, formerly the bishop of Tapachula on the Chiapas
coast, is known as a moderate with some conservative positions. He
has sharply criticized the Zapatistas for choosing to wage an armed
rebellion. Nonetheless, he also has supported Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz became known among supporters as the ''Bishop of the Poor''
for his extensive work with poverty-stricken Indian peasants. But
he was harshly criticized by the government, which linked him with
the Zapatista rebels and dubbed him the ''red bishop'' for what
they considered to be his socialist views.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Arizmendi issued a call for reconciliation -- asking
the army to respect human rights, and the rebels and the government
to make an effort to advance peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until now there has been no solution to the conflict,'' he
told the rebels Saturday. ''It seems that we are in ... a very dark
place. But I believe God will help us to encounter an adequate
solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 2034 </TRAILER>
