<HEADLINE> Explanation Of Derby Winner's Name  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus'
name is a combination of Japanese slang and Greek mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Fusao Sekiguchi came up with the first name by combining
his own first name with ''ichi,'' which in Japanese means No. 1.
Pegasus was the name of the winged horse of mythology.
</P>
<P>
   The first name is pronounced Foo-sah-EE-chee.
</P>
<P>
   Purchased for $4 million, Fusaichi Pegasus is the most expensive
winner in Derby history. The previous high price for a winner was
Winning Colors in 1998. The filly went for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The highest price horse to run in a Derby previously was
Houston, who cost $2.9 million. The colt finished eighth in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
