<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Says It Will Disarm Soon  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Uttering historic words it had
long decried as surrender, the Irish Republican Army proclaimed
Saturday that it will soon start to disarm -- a breakthrough that
makes lasting peace possible in Northern Ireland after decades of
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   The outlawed IRA, which killed about 1,800 people in its 27-year
fight to abolish Northern Ireland as a Protestant-majority state
linked to Britain, pledged to reveal its secretly stored tons of
stockpiled weapons to international arms inspectors. The process,
the IRA said, would render its arsenal ''completely and verifiably
beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments warmly welcomed the IRA's
long-sought pledge, saying it met their requirements and should
clear the way for restoring power to Northern Ireland's
Catholic-Protestant administration on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   The province had gotten a measure of self-rule when the
power-sharing administration was formed in December. But Britain
reimposed direct rule some two months later because of the IRA's
refusal to give any disarmament commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a life-and-death, blood-and-sinew, emotional, painful
step for the IRA to make -- because it wants this to work,'' said
Gerry Adams, leader of the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, President Clinton called the IRA pledge
''a significant step toward realizing the full promise of the Good
Friday Accord.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These developments offer renewed hope to the people of
Northern Ireland that politics will once and for all be pursued
through exclusively political means,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's surprise gesture came less than a day after Britain
and Ireland, as part of a concerted diplomatic push, announced they
would extend the deadline for total disarmament from this May 22 --
the target set in 1998's Good Friday peace accord -- to June 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the IRA's declaration Saturday, Britain and
Ireland announced the appointment of two international statesmen --
Cyril Ramaphosa, the former African National Congress chairman from
South Africa, and Martti Ahtisaari, Finland's recently retired
president -- to lead the arms-dump inspections. That confidential
exercise is expected to begin soon after May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ''The dumps will be reinspected regularly to ensure that the
weapons have remained silent,'' the IRA said in its statement.
Revealing these hidden stockpiles, the IRA said, should reassure
the province's British Protestant community that the IRA cease-fire
of 1997 is designed to last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the IRA had rejected the whole concept of
disarmament as equivalent to surrender. The kind of disarmament now
being offered wouldn't require the IRA to hand over weapons
publicly, only to identify the locations of its secret stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of the fate of the arms dumps have yet to be worked
out, but they are not expected to be guarded at all times. Having
made the commitment to disarm, the IRA likely will want other
parties to accept its word of honor and to be satisfied with
periodic inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's minister for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, said
he supported plans to identify but not destroy IRA arms dumps,
since this would allow the rebels to renounce violence ''without
feeling that others are standing over them and demanding that they
surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Northern Ireland's four-party coalition resumes power
now depends on the major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists,
who are bitterly split over the merits of working alongside Sinn
Fein. The party had demanded a clear IRA pledge to disarm before it
would resume any power-sharing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, the Nobel laureate who is
supposed to lead the suspended coalition, said the IRA move did
''break new ground'' and was ''very positive.''	   But speaking after a
behind-closed-doors meeting of his party's
lawmakers, Trimble said he would need to spend days ''teasing out''
many details of the proposed disarmament scheme, ''particularly
about ensuring that weapons remain secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the IRA's weapons, including tons of the plastic
explosive Semtex, were smuggled from Libya in the mid-1980s and are
buried throughout rural parts of the neighboring Republic of
Ireland. The terms of the IRA offer appear to require state
security forces to steer clear of weapons sites and to leave
monitoring of their contents to the international inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Adams insisted the IRA offer went beyond the terms of the Good
Friday pact.
</P>
<P>
   ''The IRA doesn't have to do this. It is only doing it to try
and give some assurance to those who are nervous or genuinely
concerned,'' he said. He chided Trimble's many hard-line Protestant
critics for wanting ''the IRA totally and absolutely defeated. That
isn't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how potentially divisive the new move could prove
to Sinn Fein-IRA ranks, Adams appealed for those among his
supporters ''who are nervous about this to stay calm, to be
thoughtful.''
</P>
<P>
   After the IRA called an open-ended truce in 1997, a few senior
IRA members formed a dissident faction that strove to break the
cease-fire. The dissidents, dubbed the Real IRA by Irish media,
have been observing a fragile truce since killing 29 people in a
1998 car-bomb attack. But police and politicians fear they might
attempt a deal-wrecking new atrocity in the coming crucial weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Another splinter group, the Continuity IRA, has already mounted
several nonlethal bombings this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 2125 </TRAILER>
