<HEADLINE> Twins 6, Tigers 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The return of manager Phil Garner and third
baseman Dean Palmer didn't help the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Redman pitched seven strong innings as the Minnesota Twins
beat the Detroit 6-1 Saturday night in the first game following the
end of a pair of eight-game suspensions imposed on the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Garner and Palmer were penalized by the commissioner's office
for their roles in a bench-clearing brawl against the Chicago White
Sox on April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer went 1-for-4 and committed a two-out error on Cristian
Guzman's routine grounder in the fourth, leading to the Twins'
third run.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Juan Encarnacion extended his major league-leading
hitting streak to 18 games with an infield single in the sixth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey was 3-for-4 with three singles for the Twins, and
Matt Lawton had a two-run double in a three-run seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Redman (2-0), making his first start this season and the third
of his career, allowed one run and eight hits, striking out six and
walking none.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit starter C.J. Nitkowski (1-6), winless in four starts
since April 14, allowed six runs -- five earned -- seven hits and
four walks in 6 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He balked home Minnesota's first run in the second with Huskey
on third. Jason Maxwell's RBI single and Palmer's error made it 3-0
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Deivi Cruz hit an RBI grounder in the fifth following Wendell
Magee's double.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Magee left in the seventh with an injury that was not
immediately known. ... After not facing a left-handed starter in
the first 12 games of the season, Detroit faced its eighth in 15
games. ... The Tigers were 4-4 under interim manager Bob Melvin
during Garner's absence. ... Twins manager Tom Kelly needs one win
to reach 1,000. ... Twins C Matt LeCroy caught a foul ball off the
speaker behind home plate in the third inning; on Friday night he
was unable to do the same and Bobby Higginson homered two pitches
later. ... Hunter lost a ball to center in the ceiling in the
second, resulting in a double for Higginson.
</P>
