<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians Resume Talks  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- An American envoy was expected to intervene in
Middle East peace talks after Palestinian negotiators on Saturday
rejected Israeli proposals for a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli negotiator Oded Eran met his Palestinian counterparts
Yasser Abed Rabbo and Saeb Erekat for continued talks Saturday
night, with American envoy Dennis Ross present, U.S. embassy
spokesman Larry Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting the Palestinians categorically rejected a map
submitted by Israel with a proposal for the boundaries of a
Palestinian state, said a Palestinian official, speaking on
condition of anonymity. The Palestinians say the land being offered
to them by Israel in the West Bank is totally inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides will not meet Sunday but Ross will have meetings
with each of them in an attempt to solve the dispute, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a strong possibility of a summit meeting Sunday
between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian official said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's spokesman Gadi Baltiansky said he could not rule out the
possibility that the two leaders would meet soon.
</P>
<P>
   At their last meeting Barak offered to hand over three
Palestinian neighborhoods just outside Jerusalem to full
Palestinian control, the official said, but the handover has been
delayed due to opposition inside Barak's coalition, and Arafat
wishes to raise the issue with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Israeli and Palestinian security officials met Saturday
night at Arafat's office, a Palestinian official said. At the
meeting, the outgoing chief of Israel's Shin Bet security service
introduced his successor to his Palestinian counterparts, said the
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the angry political disputes between the two sides,
Israeli officials concede that the Palestinians are making
considerable efforts to prevent attacks on Israelis by Palestinian
militants.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian police chief Ghazi Jebali announced Saturday that
two opposition figures had been arrested for incitement against the
Palestinian Authority and the peace process with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In custody were Abdullah Shami, spokesman for the militant
Islamic Jihad group and Omar Assaf, a leader of the Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a radical group based in
Damascus, Syria.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven years since Israel and the Palestinians signed
their first agreement, their talks have gone from one crisis to
another and are now far behind the original schedule.
</P>
<P>
   When they signed their last agreement in September, the two
sides set a target date of May 4 to agree on a framework for their
permanent settlement. Ross said they would need six to eight more
weeks to negotiate such a framework although the Palestinians say
no progress has been made so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
