<HEADLINE> Syracuse lion has only months to leave  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- A beloved lion who lost his mate in
November is now dying himself, and officials at the Rosamond
Gifford Zoo say it's not just from a broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   Bud is infected with feline immunodeficiency virus, or FIV, a
disease that has robbed his body of its ability to ward off
infections and disease. FIV is progressive, incurable and
ultimately fatal.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old lion's late companion of the same age, Iseult,
also had FIV, and may have infected Bud. Although FIV positive, the
lioness died of cancer, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo director Anne Baker said it is possible the grief Bud
suffered in losing his mate may have further weakened his body and
accelerated the advance of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said it's difficult to know how advanced the disease is,
but she estimated Bud's life span at between six and 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   He's still on exhibit at the zoo, although sometimes he looks
agitated and at other times dazed and inattentive. Sometimes he
still acts like he did in healthier times. He's being kept indoors
more now when the weather is poor.
</P>
<P>
   Lions are social animals, but the illness has stalled the search
for a new mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The roaring and pacing and agitation that Bud displayed after
Iseult died has ceased,'' Baker said. ''Now there's a possibility
that a new lioness would stress him more than being alone.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the fear Bud would pass the disease on to a new
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Bud stops eating and wanting to go outside, he will be
letting us know it's time to consider euthanasia,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Lions live to an average age of 13 in captivity, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-06-00 2155 </TRAILER>
