<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Revolution 2, Earthquake 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Mauricio Ramos and Wolde Harris each had a
goal and an assist as New England beat San Jose 2-1 to extend its
unbeaten streak to four.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution (2-2-4) took over first place in the MLS's
Eastern Division.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos and Harris, who assisted on each other's goals, scored
within three minutes of each other early in the second half to give
New England a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos notched his first goal off a pass from Harris at 54:11,
chipping in a shot following a giveaway by San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos fed Harris off a perfect give-and-go play at 57:10.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose (2-4-2) cut the deficit to 2-1 in the 72nd minute when
Abdul Thompson Conteh chipped an 18-yard shot over Revolution
goalkeeper Jeff Causey. The goal snapped a four-match, 352-minute
scoreless streak on the road for the Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose -- outshot 10-1 in the first half -- played without
leading scorer Ron Cerritos, who was on call for the El Salvador
national team.
</P>
<P>
   New England's Johnny Torres nearly put the Revolution ahead late
in the first half with a header off Ramos' corner kick in the 44th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose barely missed a goal six minutes into the second half
when Khodadad Azizi blasted a left-footed shot off the crossbar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
