<HEADLINE> Notes From Saturday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Indians-Blue Jays:
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: The Indians are 1-5 in May. ... Steve Karsay has five
saves in six chances. ... Jaret Wright has not won since April 12
at Oakland, a span of four starts. ... Richie Sexson doubled his
RBIs total for the season when he hit a two-run double in the first
inning. Sexson said he's spent numerous hours in the batting cage
working on his swing. ''My hands are killing me from all the
hitting I've been doing,'' said Sexson, who has six hits in his
last 10 at bats.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Ten of Carlos Delgado's 11 home runs have come at
SkyDome. ... A home run has been in hit all 17 games at SkyDome
this season. ... The Blue Jays ERA at home is 7.18. ... Toronto has
won seven of its last 10 home games.
Orioles-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Brady Anderson did not start, but made a
pinch-running appearance in the ninth. Manager Mike Hargrove said
Anderson's legs were a bit sore, but that the center fielder should
be ready Sunday. ... Mike Bordick has a 10-game hitting streak. He
began the season with a 13-game string.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Roger Clemens leads all active pitchers with 250 wins.
Atlanta's Greg Maddux is second with 225. Clemens needs one more
win to tie Bob Gibson for 38th place on the career list. ...
Manager Joe Torre got his 1,314th victory, moving him past Ned
Hanlon for 24th place. ... The Yankees have won 24 of their last 32
games against Baltimore.
Devil Rays-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Steve Trachsel pitched Tampa Bay's first complete
game since Rolando Arrojo last Aug. 27, and only the fifth in Devil
Rays history. ... Tampa Bay is 3-0 in 1-0 games. ... Vinny Castilla
is 0-for-15 with nine strikeouts against Pedro Martinez in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Pedro Martinez has struck out 10 or more batters for the
58th time in his career. He has struck out 15 or more batters seven
times. ... The 17 strikeouts is the most for a losing pitcher since
Arizona's Randy Johnson fanned 17 on June 30 against Cincinnati.
It's the most for a losing Boston pitcher since Bill Monbouquette
struck out 17 on Sept. 12, 1961.
Athletics-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: The 16 runs scored by Oakland in Friday's 17-16 loss
set an AL record for most runs in a nine-inning loss. The major
league record was set in 1922 when the Philadelphia Phillies lost
26-23 to the Chicago Cubs. ... The game also tied thmajor league
record for second-highest score in a one-run game. The record was
set on May 17, 1979, when the Philadelphia Phillies beat the
Chicago Cubs 23-22 in 10 innings at Wrigley Field. ... The 33
combined runs broke an Oakland club record. It is three short of
the franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers have won four of their last five after
opening the season 8-15. ... Rookies Tom Evans, Mike Lamb, Ruben
Mateo and Scott Sheldon were a combined 9-for-14 with seven RBIs
Friday. Rangers rookies were 3-for-20 with one RBI in all of 1998.
... The Rangers purchased the contract of Scarborugh Green from
Oklahoma of the Pacific Coast League prior to Saturday's game. They
also optioned SS Kelly Dransfeldt to Oklahoma and designated
RedHawks C Cesar King for assignment.
White Sox-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Manager Jerry Manuel served the final game of his
eight-game suspension stemming from the bench-clearing brawl versus
the Tigers April 22. Outfielder Magglio Ordonez served the last
game of his five-game suspension. Also serving a suspension during
this game was pitcher Keith Foulke. Three players have served
three-game suspensions, and pitcher Jim Parque is yet to serve his
three-game suspension. ... The White Sox and the Royals split 12
games last season, with each team winning four of six on the road.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: OF Carlos Beltran was held out of his second
straight game with a sprained left wrist. He is day to day. ... The
Royals will welcome new owner David Glass and his family before
Sunday's game. Glass will be joined in the festivities by his wife,
Ruth, sons Dan and Don and daughter Dayna Martz and his
grandchildren. Dan Glass is the Royals new president. Commissioner
Bud Selig will speak to the crowd, as will Kansas City mayor Kay
Barnes, Julia Irene Kauffman, daughter of former owners Ewing and
Muriel Kauffman, and Royals Hall of Famer George Brett.
Tigers-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Dean Palmer, in his first game back from an eight-game
suspension, played third base and hit in his familiar fifth spot in
the Tigers lineup. ... After not facing a left-handed starter in
the first 12 games of the season, Detroit faced its eighth in 15
games Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins leads the AL in doubles with 68 and have
hit two-baggers in 28 of 30 games this season. ... Jacque Jones,
who did not start Saturday night, is hitting .452 in his last 10
games with homers in the last two.
Angels-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Darin Erstad of the Angels is 1-for-9 in the first two
games of the Mariners' series and is 3-for-21 on Anaheim's road
trip. That's dropped his AL-leading batting average from .449 to
.398. ... Angels 2B Adam Kennedy almost collided with RF Tim Salmon
when he made a back-to-the-plate catch of Bell's pop for the first
out in the third. ... Salmon is 4-for-5 with a homer, three RBIs
and three walks in the Mariners series.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: Seattle's Stan Javier and Alex Rodriguez each spoke to
plate umpire Mark Wegner after being called out on strikes in the
sixth. ... In Gil Meche's six starts this season, the Mariners have
scored four runs while Meche has been in the games. ... The
Mariners played their second 1-0 game at Safeco. They lost 1-0 to
the New York Yankees last Aug. 7 when Andy Pettitte beat Freddy
Garcia. ... The Mariners played their fourth consecutive one-run
game. ... Seattle's Kazuhiro Sasaki, Japan's career saves leader,
got his first major league win. ... The last 1-0 victory for the
Mariners had been Aug. 20, 1997, against Cleveland in the Kingdome.
... Seattle got its first victory when scoring fewer than four
runs.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Pirates-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Wil Cordero continued his hitting streak, driving in
the game-tying run with his triple to the right-center wall and
going 3-for-5. He's batting .444 (8-for-18) with four RBIs in his
last four games after enduring a 2-for-25 slump. ''Not to give one
guy credit for the win, but all of the sudden, Wil's getting big
hits and generating some runs,'' manager Gene Lamont said. ''It's
surprising the difference one makes.'' ... The Pirates have a thing
about opposing closers. They've already beaten Trevor Hoffman and
Ugueth Urbina, and they knocked Rick Aguilera for four runs on two
hits in Saturday's six-run, ninth-inning rally. ... Saturday's
victory guaranteed the Pirates their first winning road trip of the
season. They're 4-1 on the six-game trip, with one game left to
play.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: There was a new guy leading the pregame stretch
Saturday morning for the Cubs' bench players -- Mark Grace. Grace
had started all but one of the first 31 games, with his lone bench
appearance coming after he took a hard fall in Cincinnati. But with
Grace mired in a 6-for-26 slump -- he was 0-for-7 the last two games
-- manager Don Baylor put him on the bench. ''In the past, when I've
watched him hit, he's always been pretty selective at the plate,''
Baylor said. ''Right now he's swinging at first pitches that are
not his pitches, he's 6-for-26, plus he needs a day off. I just
think he needs a mental break.'' Grace said his plate problems
don't have anything to do with the broken finger he suffered during
spring training. ''I just stink,'' he said. ''I know what I'm doing
wrong. We found the problem, now we just have to correct it.''
Grace came into Saturday's game in the sixth inning and went
1-for-2. ... So much for that dreaded Wrigley Field wind. In nine
games with the wind blowing in, the Cubs and their opponents have
averaged 10.1 runs and 3.1 home runs. In six games with the wind
blowing out, they've averaged 9.7 runs and 2.8 homers. ... Saturday
was the two-year anniversary of Kerry Wood's 20-strikeout game
against the Houston Astros.
Mets-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Third-base coach Cookie Rojas missed Saturday's game
because his son, Victor, was getting married. John Stearns filled
in for him. ... With LHP John Franco picking up his first save of
the season Friday night, manager Bobby Valentine said he might use
both Franco and RHP Armando Benitez in the closer role this season.
''Benitez is the closer. He will close, and so will John. If
they're both healthy, then I'll make the decision.'' ... Valentine
applauded Tommy Lasorda being hired as manager of the U.S. Olympic
baseball team: ''It's a great thing for Olympic baseball. He's
still the most recognizable baseball figure in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: The Marlins are 0-3 against former teammates in the
last week. They lost to RHP Kevin Brown and the Dodgers 7-1 last
Sunday, RHP Brian Meadows and the Padres 3-1 on Wednesday and LHP
Al Leiter and the Mets 4-1 on Friday. ... RHP A.J. Burnett had the
cast removed from his surgically repaired thumb this week and has
begun rehabilitation work. He expects to throw in 7-10 weeks. ...
Don't expect manager John Boles to make any drastic lineup changes
any time soon, even with the Marlins' recent slump. ''The last
thing in the world we want to do is give up on people,'' Boles
said. ''I just don't think that's the right thing to do.''
Cardinals-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Mark McGwire received permission to miss Saturday's
game so he could handle a personal matter. He's expected back
Sunday. ... Jim Edmonds was 0-for-2 with a pair of walks, ending
his hitting streak at seven games. He made his third start of the
season in place of McGwire at first base. ... St. Louis is 9-1 in
day games, 10-10 at night.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: The Reds put right-hander Pete Harnisch on the
disabled list, two days after he lasted only one-third of an inning
in a 14-1 loss in Philadelphia. A test detected weakness in the
back of his shoulder, and he's expected to be out for three or four
weeks. ... The Reds don't need another starter until next Saturday.
Osvaldo Fernandez is the leading candidate for a call-up from
Triple-A. ... The Reds gave out roughly 10,000 Pokey Bears, named
for their Gold Glove second baseman.
Phillies-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Mickey Morandini, who didn't play Friday against
LHP Tom Glavine, returned to the lineup with RHP Kevin Millwood on
the mound for the Braves. Morandini entered the game with the
highest average (.433) in the four-year history of Turner Field for
those with a minimum of 50 at-bats. ... The Phillies have scored on
18 runs in Randy Wolf's six starts, tied for second lowest in the
NL for five starts. ... The Phillies will stop in Reading, Pa., on
Monday for an exhibition game against their Double-A farm team.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: RF Brian Jordan was scratched from the lineup because
of lingering pain in his left side. He strained a muscle in his rib
cage while taking indoor batting practice in Los Angeles on
Tuesday. Jordan already has spent 15 days on the disabled list for
a strained muscle in his right rib cage. ... With Jordan out,
Andruw Jones was the only regular member of the outfield who
started Saturday. LF Reggie Sanders was placed on the 15-day
disabled list, retroactive to April 30, because of a sprained left
ankle. Trenidad Hubbard started in right and Bobby Bonilla was in
left. ... The Braves purchased the contract of INF Steve Sisco, who
was playing at Triple-A Richmond after hitting five homers in
spring training. ... Jonathan Schuerholz, son of Braves GM John
Schuerholz, is making a name for himself at Auburn. The younger
Schuerholz, a freshman shortstop, hit a grand slam in the eighth
inning Saturday to give the Tigers a 6-3 victory over rival
Alabama.
Expos-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Vladimir Guerrero struck out in the first inning, just
his fifth strikeout in 101 at-bats. Guerrero raised his average
from .400 to .420 by going 4-for-5 on Friday night. ... The Expos'
pitching staff combined for a season-high 14 strikeouts on Friday
night, including four in the ninth inning. Milwaukee's Luis Lopez
was struck out by Ugueth Urbina with the bases loaded in the ninth,
but he reached first and Tyler Houston scored on a wild pitch. ...
RHP Mike Thurman will make his season debut against the Cubs next
Saturday. Thurman, who went 7-11 with a 4.05 ERA for Montreal last
season, will make a rehab start for Triple-A Ottawa on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Saturday's game was the last Saturday afternoon game
scheduled at County Stadium, which is to be torn down and replaced
by Miller Park after this season. ... Wearing a Brewers batting
practice cap, Milwaukee Bucks star Ray Allen threw out the first
pitch Saturday. ... RHP Jamey Wright was scheduled to make his
first rehab start with Double-A Huntsville on Saturday. Wright,
acquired in an offseason trade and expected to be in the Brewers'
starting lineup, suffered a small rotator cuff tear during spring
training.
Padres-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Ed Sprague went 4-for-4 with two home runs against
the Diamondbacks, the fifth four-hit game of his career. Five of
Sprague's six homers this season have come against Arizona. Sprague
is hitting .579 against the Diamondbacks. ... Eric Owens was
0-for-4 and failed to reach base for the first time in the 28 games
he's played this season. ... The Padres have lost 11 of their last
13 games at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Byung-Hyun Kim, Arizona's 21-year-old sidearm reliever
from South Korea, has struck out seven consecutive batters over
three games, the longest streak in the franchise's three-year
history. He is averaging 14.2 strikeouts per nine innings. ...
Closer Matt Mantei is using the same exercise regimen to strengthen
his right shoulder as Todd Stottlemyre used to come back from a
partially torn rotator cuff without surgery.
Rockies-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Jeff Cirillo has a 13-game hitting streak for
Colorado. ... He is 22 for his last 49 (.449) with four doubles, a
triple and 11 RBIs. ... Outfielder Thomas Goodwin is expected to
rejoin the starting lineup Sunday for Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Five of Shawn Estes' six career complete games
have been shutouts. ... Estes is 8-2 in 15 career day game starts.
... Giants pitchers are working on a 21-inning scoreless streak.
They have allowed only two runs over the last 31 innings. ... The
Giants have won eight straight home games against the Rockies.
Astros-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Jeff Bagwell's home run and single on Friday night
against Kevin Brown gave him 100 career hits against the Dodgers.
Bagwell, who has at least 100 hits against 10 different teams,
needs seven more against Montreal to make it 11.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: One day after being hired as manager of the U.S.
Olympic baseball team, Dodgers senior vice president Tom Lasorda
was presented with his official U.S. jersey and cap by selection
committee co-chairmen Bob Watson and Bill Bavasi. ''Tommy cost me a
couple of World Series rings in 1981 (with the Yankees) and 1988
(with Oakland), but I'm going to forget it if he can get me the
gold,'' Watson said. ... Darren Dreifort, a month into his third
season as a major league starter, has failed to go longer than six
innings in 34 of his 60 career starts prior to Saturday night's
outing against Houston. His career was stalled by the
reconstructive surgery on his right elbow that forced him to sit
out the entire 1995 season.
</P>
