<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hispanics remember O'Connor as a true friend  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor was remembered Saturday
by his Hispanic parishioners as a friend who cared very much for
them, especially the immigrants, as they struggled to make a new
life in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the politicians, to the police, to all the nationalities
represented here today -- we are all brothers today, in respect for
the cardinal,'' said Bishop Francisco Garmendia at a Mass said in
Spanish at St. Patrick's Cathedral. ''We want to thank you,
cardinal, for all you did for us in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   People from Mexico, the Dominican Republic, Cuba, Puerto Rico
and other nations filled the cathedral pews. Many fingered rosary
beads and mouthed silent prayers in tribute to their beloved
cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   All were appreciative that the Philadelphia native had embarked
on an intensive Spanish language course upon his appointment in
1984 to head the archdiocese. His fluency improved to the point
where he could give homilies in Spanish and preside at weddings and
funerals for Hispanics, Garmendia said.
</P>
<P>
   He was especially beloved by immigrants for making them feel so
welcome, said Esperanza Morales, coordinator of the Tepeyac
Association of New York, which represents Mexican immigrants. The
group held a large banner and sang quietly outside the cathedral
after Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ''He always talked to us in Spanish, and always wanted to help
us,'' Morales said. ''We loved him, we want to tell him 'Thank you'
for all he did for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are an important part of the archdiocese, making up
approximately 36 percent of its 2.4 million members. Roughly 100 of
the archdiocese's 413 parishes are predominantly Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands came to pay tribute to the cardinal, some carrying
banners and flags.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a good man, he always made us feel special,'' said
Maria Huslin, 38, of the Bronx. ''The Hispanic community was never
made to feel second to any other nationality. He treated all his
parishioners the same. He treated us with respect.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I named my son after him,'' said Manuel Escobar, 31, of
Brooklyn, carrying his 2-year-old son Juan. ''I met him once, and I
called him 'Father.' He was like a parish priest to us. We could
talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's love for his parishioners was mentioned frequently
throughout the Mass. During his homily, the Rev. Josu Iriondo
called O'Connor someone who cherished life and who fought to make
the lives of his flock better.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a lover of life, a defender of life, of the sick, of
the poor,'' said Iriondo, pastor of Church of St. Anthony of Padua,
in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Some worshippers wiped away tears at the end of the Mass, when
Garmendia mentioned how the Hispanic community was indebted to
O'Connor. Many stayed behind after the Mass to view the cardinal's
body.
</P>
<P>
   There were also several non-Hispanics in the crowd, including a
small group of women who had just run a 3.1-mile race from Times
Square to Central Park to raise money for cancer research for
women.
</P>
<P>
   ''On such a glorious day, it seemed only fitting to come and pay
tribute to such a wonderful man,'' said Becky Moranis, 28, of
Manhattan, as she walked out of the cathedral into the warm, sunny
day.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, a line of nearly 1,000 people wanting to view
the cardinal's body stood outside the cathedral, steadily moving
toward the building's entrance. The tall buildings of midtown
shaded the relaxed crowd, which included a mix of devoted followers
of the church and other passers-by who wanted to witness a moment
in history.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m. -- half an hour before St. Patrick's closed its doors
for the night -- a steady stream of people was still flowing from
the cathedral after paying their respects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-06-00 2230 </TRAILER>
