<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Royals 11, White Sox 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Johnny Damon hit a pair of two-run
homers and went 4-for-5 Saturday night to lead the Kansas City
Royals over the Chicago White Sox 11-5.
</P>
<P>
   Every Kansas City starter had at least one hit, and reliever
Jerry Spradlin (1-1) allowed two hits in four shutout innings,
helping send the AL Central-leading White Sox to their fifth loss
in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (15-15) reached .500 for the first time since it was
8-8 on April 19. The Royals, 13-4 at home this season, finished
with a season-high 18 hits, including Mark Quinn's eighth-inning
homer off Kelly Wunsch.
</P>
<P>
   Damon, who matched his career high for hits, tied the score at 2
in the third with a homer off Mike Sirotka (2-3). Mike Sweeney
singled with two outs and scored the go-ahead run on Jermaine Dye's
triple, and Quinn followed with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   David McCarty homered leading off the fourth and Damon homered
for a 7-2 lead, chasing Sirotka, who allowed seven runs and nine
hits in 3 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was Damon's second multihomer game. The first was at
Cincinnati on June 23, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyre relieved and gave up five consecutive hits, including
run-scoring singles by Dye and Quinn, and Randa's RBI triple.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Durbin, staked to a 10-2 lead after four innings, couldn't
get out of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up Jeff Abbott's RBI double in the second, escaping a
bases-loaded jam when Carlos Lee and Greg Norton flied out, then
allowed Frank Thomas' run-scoring single in the third.
</P>
<P>
   After RBI single by Paul Konerko and Chris Singleton in the
fifth, Spadlin relieved, allowing a run-scoring, double-play
grounder to Lee.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Damon led off his ninth straight game with a base hit. He
was forced at second on a fielder's choice, failing to score in the
first inning for just the second time in the nine games. The streak
is the longest in the major leagues in at least 25 years, as Elias
Sports Bureau did not keep this stat before 1975. .... The Royals
have 57 hits in their last four games and have been in double
figures in 10 of their last 11.... The White Sox had homered in
five consecutive games coming in. ... It was just the third game
this season tthe Royals did not give up a home run.
</P>
</TEXT>
