<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Receives Ellis Island Medal  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLIS ISLAND, N.Y. (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno was among
130 people honored Saturday night at an annual celebration of the
nation's rich ethnic diversity held on Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from the historic site where thousands of immigrants
once arrived to enter the United States, Reno alluded to the case
of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban boy. She said that in the
pursuit of justice, conflicts cannot always be avoided, leaving
some people feeling betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time to rebuild trust, she said, adding, ''Let us
reach out to start to listen to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the Hudson River in Jersey City, N.J., about 100
Cuban-Americans chanted ''Reno, Repent!'' and ''Reno, Resign!''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were angry over Reno's approval of the raid on
the home of Elian's Miami relatives two weeks ago. Federal agents
seized him after the relatives refused orders by the Justice
Department to turn him over to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters gathered at the edge of a foot bridge to Ellis
Island, but were not permitted across to the area where Reno
received the award. The protest was peaceful. About 20 park rangers
and police officers were on hand to provide security.
</P>
<P>
   West New York Mayor Albio Sires said even though the
demonstrators were kept away from the awards site, they'd still
make their presence known.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know we're far away, and she might not hear us,'' he said.
''But I think the fact that so many people are here sends a
message.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy involving the Cuban boy seemed lost on the
celebrants at the awards ceremony. The event was sponsored by the
National Ethnic Coalition Organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-06-00 2358 </TRAILER>
